# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-sumner
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 30 to December 2, 1840.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the shadow of an incomplete economic recovery from the Panic of 1837, Whig nominee William Henry Harrison defeated incumbent President Martin Van Buren of the Democratic Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The election marked the first of two Whig victories in presidential elections, but was the only one where they won a majority of the popular vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the third rematch in American history.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In 1839, the Whigs held a national convention for the first time.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 1839 Whig National Convention saw 1836 nominee William Henry Harrison defeat former Secretary of State Henry Clay and General Winfield Scott.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren faced little opposition at the 1840 Democratic National Convention, but controversial Vice President Richard Mentor Johnson was not renominated.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats thus became the only major party since 1800 to fail to select a vice presidential nominee.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Referencing vice presidential nominee John Tyler and Harrison's participation in the Battle of Tippecanoe, the Whigs campaigned on the slogan of "Tippecanoe and Tyler Too." With Van Buren weakened by economic woes, Harrison won a popular majority and 234 of 294 electoral votes.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Voter participation surged as white male suffrage became nearly universal, and a contemporary record of 42.4% of the voting age population voted for Harrison.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren's loss made him the third president to lose re-election.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs did not enjoy the benefits of victory.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 67-year-old Harrison, the oldest U.S. president elected until Ronald Reagan won the 1980 election, died a little more than a month after inauguration.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison was succeeded by John Tyler, who unexpectedly proved not to be a Whig.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] While Tyler had been a staunch supporter of Clay at the convention, he was a former Democrat, a passionate supporter of states' rights, and effectively an independent.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] As President, Tyler blocked the Whigs' legislative agenda and was expelled from the Whig Party, subsequently the second independent (after Washington) to serve as president.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren would be the last incumbent president to lose his reelection bid in a general election until fellow Democrat Grover Cleveland in 1888.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last time a challenger to an incumbent president got a majority of the vote until 1932.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last time as of 2024 where the incumbent president seeking re-election flipped a state yet failed to secure re-election, with Van Buren winning South Carolina, despite losing it four years earlier, and losing re-election to Harrison.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The first national convention of the Whig Party was called for by members of the party in Congress and it was attended by almost 250 delegates in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, William Henry Harrison, and Winfield Scott ran for the party's presidential nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The delegations of each state balloted separately before meeting together with the other representatives of the states.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Clay initially led on the first ballot, but Harrison won on the final ballot with 148 votes compared to Clay's 90 votes and Scott's 16 votes after supporters from Scott switched to Harrison.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] John Tyler was selected as a factional and geographical balance to Harrison.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic members of the New Hampshire General Court made a call for the 1840 Democratic National Convention which was held in Baltimore, Maryland in May 1840.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Delegates from twenty-two states attended the convention, but the sizes of the delegations varied with New Jersey having fifty-nine delegates to cast its eight votes while Massachusetts only had one delegate to cast its fourteen votes.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] A committee was formed to make recommendations for the nominations and the committee supported Van Buren for renomination which was approved by acclamation.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, the vice-presidential nomination was left vacant due to opposition to Vice President Richard Mentor Johnson's personal life.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] After the negative views of Freemasonry among a large segment of the public began to wane in the mid-1830s, the Anti-Masonic Party disintegrated.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Many leaders began to move to the Whig party.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Remaining leaders met in September 1837 in Washington, and agreed to maintain the party.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The third Anti-Masonic Party National Convention was held in Philadelphia on November 13–14, 1838.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] By this time, the party had been almost entirely supplanted by the Whigs.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates unanimously voted to nominate William Henry Harrison for president (who the party had supported for president the previous election along with Francis Granger for vice president) and Daniel Webster for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, when the Whig National Convention nominated Harrison with John Tyler as his running mate, the Anti-Masonic Party did not make an alternate nomination and ceased to function and was fully absorbed into the Whigs by 1840.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Birney, Myron Holley, Joshua Leavitt, and Gerrit Smith proposed the creation of an anti-slavery party.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In July 1839, two resolutions proposed by Holley at the American Anti-Slavery Society's meeting in Cleveland, called for the creation of an abolitionist party.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Nevertheless, the supporters nominated Birney and Francis Julius LeMoyne as a presidential ticket at a meeting in Warsaw, New York.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, Birney declined the presidential nomination as he preferred a nomination to be made by a regular body of abolitionists and LeMoyne also declined the vice-presidential nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Smith and Holley made a call for an abolitionist nominating convention to be held on April 1, 1840, in Albany, New York.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] 121 delegates attended the delegation and selected a presidential ticket of Birney and Thomas Earle. which was accepted.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Birney was unable to campaign during the election as he was in England until November.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Liberty Party received opposition from followers of William Lloyd Garrison and abolitionist Whigs.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the wake of the Panic of 1837, Van Buren was widely unpopular, and Harrison, following Andrew Jackson's strategy, ran as a war hero and man of the people while presenting Van Buren as a wealthy snob living in luxury at the public expense.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Although Harrison was comfortably wealthy and well educated, his "log cabin" image caught fire, sweeping all sections of the country.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison avoided campaigning on the issues, with his Whig Party attracting a broad coalition with few common ideals.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig strategy overall was to win the election by avoiding discussion of difficult national issues such as slavery or the national bank and concentrate instead on exploiting dissatisfaction over the failed policies of the Van Buren administration with colorful campaigning techniques.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison was the first president to campaign actively for office.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] He did so with the slogan "Tippecanoe and Tyler too".
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Tippecanoe referred to Harrison's military victory over a group of Shawnee Native Americans at a river in Indiana called Tippecanoe in 1811.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] For their part, Democrats laughed at Harrison for being too old for the presidency, and referred to him as "Granny", hinting that he was senile.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs took advantage of this quip and declared that Harrison was "the log cabin and hard cider candidate", a man of the common people from the rough-and-tumble West.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] They depicted Harrison's opponent, President Martin Van Buren, as a wealthy snob who was out of touch with the people.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, it was Harrison who came from a family of wealthy planters, while Van Buren's father was a tavernkeeper.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison however moved to the frontier and for years lived in a log cabin, while Van Buren had been a well-paid government official.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, the election was held in the wake of the Panic of 1837, one of the worst economic depressions in the nation's history, and voters blamed Van Buren, seeing him as unsympathetic to struggling citizens.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] 31.9% of the voting age population and 80.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time that a majority of southern voters participated in the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison won the support of western settlers and eastern bankers alike.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,179 counties/independent cities making returns, Harrison won in 699 (59.29%) while Van Buren carried 477 (40.46%).
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Three counties (0.25%) in the South split evenly between Harrison and Van Buren.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The extent of Van Buren's unpopularity was evident in Harrison's victories in New York, the president's home state, and in Tennessee, where Andrew Jackson himself had come out of retirement to stump for his former vice-president.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time a Democratic president lost re-election, as well as the first of only two times (the other being 1980) that a Democratic president lost re-election and lost the popular vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the first election in U.S. history in which a candidate won more than a million popular votes.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election where Indiana voted for the Whigs.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only election where the Whigs won Maine, Michigan, and Mississippi.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only election in American history in which a majority of voters in Alabama and a majority of voters in Mississippi voted for different candidates.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 1840 presidential election was the only time in which four people who either had been or would become a U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] President (Van Buren, Harrison, Tyler, and Polk) received at least one vote in the Electoral College when it voted for president and vice-president.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison's victory won him precious little time as chief executive of the United States.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] After giving the longest inauguration speech in U.S. history (lasting about 1 hour and 45 minutes, in cold weather and rain), Harrison served only one month as president before dying of pneumonia on April 4, 1841.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Source: Data from Walter Dean Burnham, *Presidential ballots, 1836–1892* (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1955) pp 247–257.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the 1997 film *Amistad*, Van Buren (played by Nigel Hawthorne) is seen campaigning for re-election.
[src:charles-sumner/1840-united-states-presidential-election] These scenes have been criticized for their historical inaccuracy.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 1 to December 4, 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk narrowly defeated Whig nominee Henry Clay in a close contest turning on the controversial issues of slavery and the annexation of the Republic of Texas.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only election in which both major party nominees served as Speaker of the House at one point, and the first in which neither candidate held elective office at the time.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] President John Tyler's pursuit of Texas annexation divided both major parties.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Annexation would geographically expand American slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It also risked war with Mexico while the United States engaged in sensitive possession and boundary negotiations with Great Britain, which controlled Canada, over Oregon.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Texas annexation thus posed both domestic and foreign policy risks.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Both major parties had wings in the North and the South, but the possibility of the expansion of slavery threatened a sectional split in each party.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Expelled by the Whig Party after vetoing key Whig legislation and lacking a firm political base, Tyler hoped to use the annexation of Texas to win the presidency as an independent or at least to have decisive, pro-Texas influence over the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The initial frontrunner for the Democratic nomination was former President Martin Van Buren, but his opposition to the annexation of Texas damaged his candidacy.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Opposition from former President Andrew Jackson and most Southern delegations, plus a nomination rule change specifically aimed to block him, prevented Van Buren from winning the necessary two-thirds vote of delegates to the 1844 Democratic National Convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk, former Governor of Tennessee and Speaker.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He was the first successful dark horse for the presidency.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk ran on a platform embracing popular commitment to expansion, often referred to as Manifest Destiny.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler dropped out of the race and endorsed Polk.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs nominated Henry Clay, a famous, long-time party leader who was the early favorite but who conspicuously waffled on Texas annexation.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Though a Southerner from Kentucky and a slave owner, Clay chose to focus on the risks of annexation while claiming not to oppose it personally.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His awkward, repeated attempts to adjust and finesse his position on Texas confused and alienated voters, contrasting negatively with Polk's consistent clarity.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk successfully linked the dispute with Britain over Oregon with the Texas issue.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic nominee thus united anti-slavery Northern expansionists, who demanded Oregon, with pro-slavery Southern expansionists who demanded Texas.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In the national popular vote, Polk beat Clay by fewer than 40,000 votes, a margin of 1.4%.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Birney of the anti-slavery Liberty Party won 2.3% of the vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Electoral College winner was decided by New York where Polk won by just over 5,100 votes.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Had Clay won the state, he would have won the presidency with 141 electoral votes to Polk's 134.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Birney's vote share in New York exceeded Polk's margin of victory over Clay, marking the first time a third party candidate vote share exceeded the margin of a winning candidate in a decisive state. of a United States presidential election.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] After Polk's victory, Tyler annexed Texas, which was the proximate cause of the Mexican–American War during Polk's presidency.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs and Democrats embarked upon their campaigns during the climax of the congressional gag rule controversies in 1844, which prompted Southern congressmen to suppress northern petitions to end the slave trade in the District of Columbia.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-annexation petitions to Congress sent from northern anti-slavery forces, including state legislatures, were similarly suppressed.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Intra-party sectional compromises and maneuvering on slavery politics during these divisive debates placed significant strain on the northern and southern wings that comprised each political organization.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The question as to whether the institution of slavery and its aristocratic principles of social authority were compatible with democratic republicanism was becoming "a permanent issue in national politics".
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In 1836, a portion of the Mexican state of Coahuila y Tejas declared its independence to form the Republic of Texas.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Texans, mostly American immigrants from the Deep South, many of whom owned slaves, sought to bring their republic into the Union as a state.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] At first, the subject of annexing Texas to the United States was shunned by both major American political parties.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Although they recognized Texas sovereignty, Presidents Andrew Jackson (1829–1837) and Martin Van Buren (1837–1841) declined to pursue annexation.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The prospect of bringing another slave state into the Union was fraught with problems.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Both major parties – the Democrats and Whigs – viewed Texas statehood as something "not worth a foreign war [with Mexico]" or the "sectional combat" that annexation would provoke in the United States.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The incumbent President John Tyler, formerly vice-president, had assumed the presidency upon the death of William Henry Harrison in 1841.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler, a Whig in name only, emerged as a states' rights advocate committed to slavery expansion in defiance of Whig principles.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] After he vetoed the Whig domestic legislative agenda, he was expelled from his own party on September 13, 1841.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Politically isolated, but unencumbered by party restraints, Tyler aligned himself with a small faction of Texas annexationists in a bid for election to a full term in 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler became convinced that Great Britain was encouraging a Texas–Mexico rapprochement that might lead to slave emancipation in the Texas republic.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Accordingly, he directed Secretary of State Abel P.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Upshur of Virginia to initiate, then relentlessly pursue, secret annexation talks with Texas minister to the United States Isaac Van Zandt, beginning on October 16, 1843.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler submitted his Texas-U.S. treaty for annexation to the U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Senate, delivered April 22, 1844, where a two-thirds majority was required for ratification.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The newly appointed Secretary of State John C.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun of South Carolina (assuming his post March 29, 1844) included a document known as the Packenham Letter with the Tyler bill that was calculated to inject a sense of crisis in Southern Democrats of the Deep South.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In it, he characterized slavery as a social blessing and the acquisition of Texas as an emergency measure necessary to safeguard the "peculiar institution" in the United States.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In doing so, Tyler and Calhoun sought to unite the South in a crusade that would present the North with an ultimatum: support Texas annexation or lose the South.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-slavery Whigs considered Texas annexation particularly egregious, since Mexico had outlawed slavery in Coahuila y Tejas in 1829, before Texas independence had been declared.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The 1844 presidential campaigns evolved within the context of this struggle over Texas annexation, which was tied to the question of slavery expansion and national security.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] All candidates in the 1844 presidential election had to declare a position on this explosive issue.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Martin Van Buren, President of the United States between 1837 and 1841, and chief architect of Jacksonian democracy, was the presumptive Democratic presidential contender in the spring of 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun withdrawing his bid for the presidency in January 1844, the campaign was expected to focus on domestic issues.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren regarded the Tyler annexation measure as an attempt to sabotage his bid for the White House by exacerbating the already strained North-South Democratic alliance regarding slavery expansion.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The annexation of Texas was the chief political issue of the day.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren, initially the leading candidate, opposed immediate annexation because it might lead to a sectional crisis over the status of slavery in the West and lead to war with Mexico.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This position cost Van Buren the support of southern and expansionist Democrats; as a result, he failed to win the nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates likewise could not settle on Lewis Cass, the former Secretary of War, whose credentials also included past service as a U.S. minister to France.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On the eighth ballot, the historian George Bancroft, a delegate from Massachusetts, proposed former House Speaker James K.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk argued that Texas and Oregon had always belonged to the United States by right.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He called for "the immediate re-annexation of Texas" and for the "re-occupation" of the disputed Oregon territory.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On the next roll call, the convention unanimously accepted Polk, who became the first dark horse, or little-known, presidential candidate.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates selected Senator Silas Wright of New York for Vice President, but Wright, an admirer of Van Buren, declined the nomination to become the second person to decline a vice presidential nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren realized that accommodating slavery expansionists in the South would open the Northern Democrats to charges of appeasement to the Slave power from the strongly anti-annexation Northern Whigs and some Democrats.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He crafted an emphatically anti-Texas position that temporized with expansionist southern Democrats, laying out a highly conditional scenario that delayed Texas annexation indefinitely.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In the Hammett letter, published April 27, 1844 (penned April 20), he counseled his party to reject Texas under a Tyler administration.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Furthermore, annexation of Texas as a territory would proceed, tentatively, under a Van Buren administration, only when the American public had been consulted on the matter and Mexico's cooperation had been pursued to avoid an unnecessary war.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A military option might be advanced if a groundswell of popular support arose for Texas, certified with a congressional mandate.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In these respects, Martin Van Buren differed from Henry Clay, who would never tolerate annexation without Mexico's assent.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] With the publication of Clay's Raleigh Letter and Van Buren's Hammett letter, Van Burenite Democrats hoped that their candidate's posture on Texas would leave southern pro-annexationists with exactly one choice for president: Martin Van Buren.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In this, they misjudged the political situation.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler and the southern pro-annexationists posed a potentially far greater threat than Clay, in that the Tyler-Calhoun treaty would put immense pressure on the northern Democrats to comply with southern Democrats' demands for Texas.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Hammett letter utterly failed to reassure Middle and Deep South extremists who had responded favorably to Calhoun's Pakenham Letter.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A minority of the southern Democrat leadership remained obdurate that Northern Democratic legislators would ignore their constituents' opposition to slavery expansion and unite in support of Texas annexation once exposed to sufficient southern pressure.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Former President Andrew Jackson publicly announced his support for immediate Texas annexation in May 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had facilitated Tyler's Texas negotiations in February 1844 by reassuring Sam Houston, the President of Texas, that the U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] As the Senate debated the Tyler treaty, Jackson declared that the popular support among Texans for annexation should be respected, and any delay would result in a British dominated Texas Republic that would promote slave emancipation and pose a foreign military threat to the southwest United States.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The former military hero went further, urging all Jacksonian Democrats to block Martin Van Buren from the party ticket and seek a Democratic presidential candidate fully committed to the immediate annexation of Texas.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In doing so, Jackson abandoned the traditional Jeffersonian-Jacksonian formula that had required its Northern and Southern wings to compromise on constitutional slavery disputes.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Texas issue was fracturing Van Buren's support among Democrats and would derail his candidacy.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk furthermore pledged to serve only one term as president.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He would keep this promise, and would die less than three months after leaving office.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The annexation treaty needed a two-thirds vote and was easily defeated in the Senate, largely along partisan lines, 16 to 35 – a two-thirds majority against passage – on June 8, 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs voted 27–1 against the treaty: all northern Whig senators voted nay, and fourteen of fifteen southern Whig senators had joined them.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats voted for the treaty 15–8, with a slight majority of Northern Democrats opposing.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Southern Democrats affirmed the treaty 10–1, with only one slave state senator, Thomas Hart Benton, voting against.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Three days later, Tyler and his supporters in Congress began exploring means to bypass the supermajority requirement for Senate treaty approval.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Substituting the constitutional protocols for admitting regions of the United States into the Union as states, Tyler proposed that alternative, yet constitutional, means be used to bring the Republic of Texas – a foreign country – into the Union.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler and Calhoun, formerly staunch supporters of minority safeguards based on the supermajority requirements for national legislation, now altered their position to facilitate passage of the Tyler treaty.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler's attempt to evade the Senate vote launched a spirited congressional debate.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay of Kentucky, effectively the leader of the Whig Party since its inception in 1834, was selected as its nominee at the party's convention in Baltimore, Maryland, on May 1, 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay, a slaveholder, presided over a party in which its Southern wing was sufficiently committed to the national platform to put partisan loyalties above slavery expansionist proposals that might undermine its north–south alliance.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs felt confident that Clay could duplicate Harrison's landslide victory of 1840 against any opposition candidate.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Southern Whigs feared that the acquisition of the fertile lands in Texas would produce a huge market for slave labor, inflating the price of slaves and deflating land values in their home states.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Northern Whigs feared that Texas statehood would initiate the opening of a vast "Empire for Slavery".
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Two weeks before the Whig convention in Baltimore, in reaction to Calhoun's Packenham Letter, Clay issued a document known as the Raleigh Letter (issued April 17, 1844) that presented his views on Texas to his fellow southern Whigs.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In it, he flatly denounced the Tyler annexation bill and predicted that its passage would provoke a war with Mexico, whose government had never recognized Texas independence.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay underlined his position, warning that even with Mexico's consent, he would block annexation in the event that substantial sectional opposition existed anywhere in the United States.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig party leadership was acutely aware that any proslavery legislation advanced by its southern wing would alienate its anti-slavery northern wing and cripple the party in the general election.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In order to preserve their party, Whigs would need to stand squarely against acquiring a new slave state.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] As such, Whigs were content to restrict their 1844 campaign platform to less divisive issues such as internal improvements and national finance.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs picked Theodore Frelinghuysen of New Jersey – "the Christian Statesman" – as Clay's running mate.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] An advocate of the colonization of emancipated slaves, he was acceptable to southern Whigs as an opponent of the abolitionists.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His pious reputation balanced Clay's image as a slave-holding, hard-drinking duelist.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On July 27, 1844, Clay released a position statement, the so-called "Alabama Letter." In it, he counseled his Whig constituency to regard Texas annexation and statehood as merely a short phase in the decline of slavery in the United States, rather than a long term advance for the Slave Power.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay qualified his stance on Texas annexation, declaring "no personal objection to the annexation" of the republic.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He would move back to his original orientation in September 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Northern Whigs expressed outrage at any détente with the Slave Power and accused him of equivocating on Texas annexation.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay's central position, however, had not altered: no annexation without northern acquiescence.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay's commitment brought Southern Whigs under extreme pressure in their home states and congressional districts, threatening to tarnish their credentials as supporters of slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] After the closed session Senate debates on the Tyler-Texas treaty were leaked to the public on April 27, 1844, President Tyler's only hope of success in influencing passage of his treaty was to intervene directly as a spoiler candidate in the 1844 election.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His "Democratic-Republican Party", a recycling of the name of Jefferson's party, held its convention on May 27, 1844, in Baltimore, Maryland, a short distance from the unfolding Democratic Party convention that would select James K.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler was nominated the same day without challenge, accepting the honor on May 30, 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Tyler delegates did not designate a vice-presidential running mate.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk was faced with the possibility that a Tyler ticket might shift votes away from the Democrats and provide Clay with the margin of victory in a close race.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler made clear in his nomination acceptance speech that his overriding concern was the ratification of his Texas annexation treaty.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, he hinted that he would drop out of the race once that end was assured, informing Polk, through Senator Robert J.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Walker of Mississippi, that his campaign efforts were simply a vehicle to mobilize support for Texas annexation.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler concentrated his resources in the states of New York, Pennsylvania and New Jersey, all highly contested states in the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Securing enough Democratic support, his withdrawal might prove indispensable to Polk.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk was receptive as long as Tyler could withdraw without raising suspicion of a secret bargain.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] To solidify Tyler's cooperation, Polk enlisted Andrew Jackson to reassure Tyler that Texas annexation would be consummated under a Polk administration.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On August 20, 1844, Tyler dropped out of the presidential race, and Tylerites moved quickly to support the Democratic Party nominee.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Liberty Party held its 1843 national convention on August 30 in Buffalo, New York, with 148 delegates from twelve states in attendance.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Birney, the party's presidential nominee in the 1840 election, was renominated with 108 votes on the first ballot (Thomas Morris and William Jay received 2 and 1 votes respectively).
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Morris would go on to be nominated for vice-president with 83 votes compared to Gerrit Smith's 22 and Alvan Stewart's 1.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The party received 2.3% of the popular vote in the election, which was the highest it ever received.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Joseph Smith, the mayor of Nauvoo, Illinois, and founder of the Latter-day Saint movement, ran as an independent under the newly created Reform Party with Sidney Rigdon as his running mate.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His top aide Brigham Young campaigned for Smith saying, "He it is that God of Heaven designs to save this nation from destruction and preserve the Constitution." The campaign ended when he was attacked and killed by a mob while in the Carthage, Illinois, jail on June 27, 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] 30.6% of the voting age population and 79% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk's adoption of Manifest Destiny paid dividends at the polls.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] No longer identified with the Tyler-Calhoun "southern crusade for slavery", the western Democrats could embrace Texas annexation.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats enjoyed a huge upsurge in voter turnout, up to 20% over the figures from 1840, especially in the Northwest and Mid-Atlantic regions.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats won Michigan, Illinois, and Indiana and nearly took Ohio, where the concept of Manifest Destiny was most admired.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In the Deep South, Clay lost every state to Polk, a huge reversal from the 1840 race, but carried most of the Middle and Border South.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay's "waffling" on Texas may have cost him the 41 electoral votes of New York and Michigan.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The former slaveholder, now abolitionist, James Birney of the Liberty Party, received 15,812 and 3,632 votes, respectively, based on his unwavering stand against Texas annexation.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Celebratory shots rang out in Washington on November 7 as returns came in from western New York which clinched the state and the presidency for Polk.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk won by a mere 5,106 out of 470,062 cast in New York, and only 3,422 out of 52,096 votes in Michigan.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Had enough of these voting blocks cast their ballots for the anti-annexationist Clay in New York, he would have defeated Polk.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Still, Clay's opposition to annexation and western slavery expansion served him well among Northern Whigs and nearly secured him the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Clay was the third of eight presidential nominees to win a significant number of electoral votes in at least three elections, the others being Thomas Jefferson, Andrew Jackson, Grover Cleveland, William Jennings Bryan, Franklin D.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, Richard Nixon, and Donald Trump.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, Jackson, Cleveland, and Roosevelt also won the popular vote in at least three elections.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay and Bryan are the only two candidates to lose the presidency three times.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This is the most recent presidential election where the election took place on different days in different states.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It is the only presidential election in which both major party nominees were former Speakers of the House.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which Ohio voted for the Whigs.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only presidential election in which the winner, Polk, lost both his birth state of North Carolina and his state of residence, Tennessee, (which he lost by only 123 votes) before Donald Trump's victory in the 2016 presidential election.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first of four times that a victorious candidate lost their home state followed by 1916, 1968, and 2016.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk's election confirmed that Manifest Destiny had majority support in the electorate despite Whig opposition.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The annexation of Texas was formalized on March 1, 1845, days before Polk took office.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Mexico refused to accept the annexation and the Mexican–American War broke out in 1846.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Instead of demanding all of Oregon, Polk compromised.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Washington and London negotiated the Buchanan–Pakenham Treaty, which split up the Oregon Territory between the two countries.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Upon the conclusion of the election, Whig publications were disheartened at Henry Clay's loss against Polk's alleged fraud.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig Almanac, a yearly collection of political statistics and events of interest to the party, contained in 1845 a column alleging fraud in Louisiana.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It noted that, in one Louisiana parish, Plaquemines, the vote tally exploded from a 240 to 40 vote victory for the Van Buren ticket in 1840 to a 1007 to 37 vote victory for the Polk ticket in 1844.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The 970 vote margin was greater than Polk's margin statewide.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The 1,007 votes received by Polk exceeded the total number of all white males in the parish in 1840, despite Louisiana having a property requirement to vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A steward, pilot, and passenger of the steamboat *Agnes* reportedly said that the ship ferried voters from New Orleans to Plaquemines parish where the steward was pushed by the Captain to vote for the Polk ticket three times, despite not being of voting age.
[src:charles-sumner/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A man named Charles Bruland was seen driven out of the voting booth wounded and bloody after attempting to cast a vote for the Clay ticket in Plaquemines Parish.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] National conventions of the **Free Soil and Liberty parties** met in 1847 and 1848 to nominate candidates for president and vice president in advance of the 1848 United States presidential election.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] These assemblies resulted in the creation of the national Free Soil Party, a union of political abolitionists with antislavery Conscience Whigs and Barnburner Democrats to oppose the westward extension of slavery into the U.S. territories.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Former President Martin Van Buren was nominated for president by the Free Soil National Convention that met at Buffalo, New York on August 9, 1848; Charles Francis Adams Sr. was nominated for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Van Buren and Adams received 291,409 popular votes in the national election, almost all from the free states; his popularity among northern Democrats was great enough to deny his Democratic rival, Lewis Cass, the crucial state of New York, throwing the state and the election to Whig Zachary Taylor.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The organizers of the Liberty Party found themselves at a crossroads following the 1844 United States elections.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The party had experienced rapid growth from 1840 to 1844, particularly in New England, where Liberty candidates were elected to state legislative offices.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In 1844, the Liberty nominees for president and vice president, James G.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Birney and Thomas Morris, received 62,025 votes in the 13 free states, representing 2.30% of the national total.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In New York and Michigan the Liberty vote was more than the margin separating Democrat James K.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] After 1844, the party's growth plateaued, and party leaders began to consider the future trajectory of the movement.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Chase, one group favored cooperation with anti-slavery Whigs and Democrats, even suggesting Liberty candidates should be willing to withdraw in favor of major party candidates who pledged opposition to slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] This strategy was most successful in New Hampshire, where in 1846 a coalition of Liberty men, Whigs, and Independent Democrats elected John P.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Others opposed any cooperation with the major parties and argued the Liberty Party should adopt a broad reform platform in order to appeal to voters outside the antislavery movement.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] This group organized the Liberty League to promote their ideas within the party and included political abolitionists such as Gerrit Smith, William Goodell, and others.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Unlike in 1844, there was no obvious candidate who could command the unanimous support of the Liberty Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] While leaders of the Liberty League hoped to persuade Birney to stand for a third time, his reputation had been damaged by missteps during the 1844 campaign, and Birney himself was disinclined to run again.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The Liberty League met at Macedon Lock, New York over June 8–10, 1847 and nominated Smith for president and Elihu Burritt for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] (Burritt declined the nomination, and the League eventually promoted Charles C.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Foote to be Smith's running mate.) Seventy delegates were in attendance, including Goodell, who presided over the meeting.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The convention adopted a platform endorsing an antislavery interpretation of the United States Constitution, free trade, abolition of the army and navy, and land reform.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Reflecting the influence of early feminists within the League, prominent female abolitionists Lydia Maria Child and Lucretia Mott received one vote apiece in the balloting for president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] A deputation from the Liberty League was present when the Liberty Party held their national convention at Buffalo, New York on October 20, 1847.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] They aimed to secure Smith's nomination by the national party on a platform accepting the resolves of the Macedon convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The faction led by Chase, meanwhile, continued to seek support from disaffected members of the two major parties.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In the months preceding the convention, they began to promote Hale as a candidate capable of uniting a broad coalition of Liberty men, Conscience Whigs, and Independent Democrats on the basis of opposition to slavery's extension.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] A contingent of Liberty leaders including Joshua Leavitt, Henry B.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Stanton, and John Greenleaf Whittier met with Hale in Boston in July 1847 to encourage him to make a public declaration of his candidacy.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Hale, however, was concerned that accepting the party's nomination would weaken his position in the Senate and asked for the convention to be delayed until the following spring.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] When the Chase faction failed to secure the delay of the convention, Hale wrote to Lewis Tappan requesting that his name not be placed in nomination at the Buffalo convention, but Tappan ignored this request.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Acceptance of Hale required a significant shift in the party's attitude and approach to politics.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Chase and his allies worked tirelessly throughout the summer in support of Hale's candidacy; their efforts were rewarded, as Hale was nominated overwhelmingly by the national convention, with 103 votes to 44 for Smith.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Former Ohio Supreme Court Justice Leicester King was nominated for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The nomination of Hale by the Liberty National Convention was a major victory for the coalitionists.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Crucially, it secured a candidate who could be persuaded to withdraw if a coalition with antislavery Whigs and Democrats were later possible.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Events in the spring of 1848 soon presented such an opportunity.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The end of the Mexican-American War raised the question of westward expansion and the extension of slavery into the U.S. territories.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In 1846, northern Whigs crossed party lines to support a proposal by David Wilmot, a Democrat from Pennsylvania, to exclude slavery from all of the territory acquired from Mexico.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The 1848 Democratic National Convention repudiated the Wilmot Proviso and nominated Lewis Cass for president on a platform endorsing popular sovereignty.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Cass's nomination enraged supporters of former President Martin Van Buren, who had been denied the nomination of his party in 1844 due to his opposition to the annexation of Texas; they considered the rejection of Van Buren evidence of the party's subservience to the Slave Power.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The 1848 Whig National Convention at Philadelphia took no position on the Wilmot Proviso, but its candidate, General Zachary Taylor, was a slaveholder from Louisiana who had risen to prominence by his exploits in a war most abolitionists considered immoral.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Abolitionists thus faced a choice between a proslavery Democrat and a slaveholding Whig.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] These conditions were ripe for a third candidate to emerge and unite the support of antislavery men of all parties, as Chase and his allies had long anticipated.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In May 1848, Barnburners in New York, predicting a Cass victory, called for a convention of anti-Cass Democrats in Utica on June 22.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] This convention nominated Van Buren for president and Senator Henry Dodge for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In the aftermath of Taylor's nomination, a contingent of disgruntled Whigs led by Massachusetts delegates Henry Wilson and Charles Allen withdrew from the Philadelphia convention and called for a new meeting of antislavery advocates at Buffalo.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Both groups recognized the importance of uniting all antislavery voters under one roof; when Dodge declined the vice presidential nomination, it opened the door for the Barnburners to join the growing free soil movement.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Members of the Liberty Party objected to Van Buren due to his opposition to the abolition of slavery in Washington, D.C. and his stance during the Amistad case.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Leavitt stated that they "cannot support him, without deliberately giving the lie to all our own declarations for fifteen years past" as Van Buren was a "Northern man with Southern principles".
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The Buffalo Free Soil convention opened on August 9 with approximately 20,000 Democrats, Whigs, and Liberty men in attendance.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Many of the Whigs hoped for the nomination of Supreme Court Justice John McLean, who had been available as a candidate for the Whig and Anti-Masonic parties in past elections.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Most Liberty men still supported Hale; but the importance of the Barnburners, by far the largest contingent of the new party, made Van Buren the early frontrunner for the nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] McLean soon found he lacked sufficient support to be nominated and withdrew his name from consideration; an informal vote within the committee of conferees found a majority in favor of Van Buren.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In exchange for Liberty support for Van Buren, Chase negotiated acceptance of much of the Liberty Party's platform, including the non-extension of slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] As a gesture to the party's Whig element, Charles Francis Adams Sr., son of the late John Quincy Adams, was nominated for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Like the Liberty platform of 1844, but unlike the more radical Liberty League document, the national platform of the Free Soil Party accepted the premise that the United States Congress had no legal or constitutional authority to abolish slavery in the slave states.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Instead, it occupied the narrower ground of opposing the admission of new slave states and territories.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The platform made no mention of the Fugitive Slave Act of 1793 or the civil and political rights of African Americans, unlike previous Liberty Party documents.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] It included planks endorsing traditional Democratic economic policies which many in the Liberty Party had long supported, including a federal homestead act, as well as public support for internal improvements.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The acolytes of the Liberty League were unimpressed by the result of the Free Soil convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] These abolitionists had objected to Hale in spite of his spirited opposition to the gag rule; they were hardly inclined to support Van Buren, who had endorsed the gag rule as president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The platform adopted by the National Liberty Party at Buffalo completed the separation of the Liberty Leaguers from the majority faction of the Liberty Party who would go on to support Van Buren and the free soil movement in the general election.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The delegates approved a preamble and thirteen resolutions rejecting the result of the "spurious" 1847 Liberty Party convention and declaring the National Liberty Party a "permanent" organization committed to universal application of the doctrine of equal rights.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In pointed contrast to the more moderate position staked out by the Free Soilers, they declared all proslavery laws and constitutions to be null and void and asserted the power and obligation of the United States Congress to abolish slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] They endorsed the free-produce movement and the recent escape attempt by 77 enslaved people in Washington, D.C.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Despite the optimism of the Free Soilers, Van Buren carried no electoral votes, finishing a distant third behind Cass and Taylor.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] His 10.13% of the popular vote, however, represents a dramatic improvement on Birney's 1844 result, owing largely to his popularity with antislavery Democrats.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The National Liberty Party attracted sparse support; Smith received votes in only four states, including his native New York, where he polled 2,454 votes (0.56%).
[src:charles-sumner/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The Free Soil platform of 1848 provided the policy basis for the antislavery coalition that would come to power in the election of 1860 as the Republican Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 7, 1848 in the aftermath of the Mexican–American War.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] General Zachary Taylor of the Whig Party defeated Senator Lewis Cass of the Democratic Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his unclear political alignment and Whig opposition to the Mexican–American War in which Taylor had led American forces to victory, the 1848 Whig National Convention nominated the popular general over party stalwarts Henry Clay and Daniel Webster.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] For vice president, the Whigs nominated Millard Fillmore from New York, known for moderate views on slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Polk, a Democrat, refused to seek re-election.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The 1848 Democratic National Convention nominated Senator Lewis Cass of Michigan after former President Martin Van Buren withdrew his bid for a third and nonconsecutive nomination over a platform dispute.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren, from New York, instead broke from the Democratic Party to win the nomination of the Free Soil Party, which opposed the extension of slavery into the territories.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats had a record of prosperity and had acquired vast lands including Texas, the Mexican Cession, and the southern portion of the Oregon Country.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] They appeared certain to win unless the Whigs masked their prior opposition to the successful war by nominating Taylor.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor won a popular plurality and an electoral majority, while Van Buren won 10.1% of the popular vote, a strong showing for a third party candidate.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor was the second Whig to win a Presidential election, following fellow general William Henry Harrison's victory in 1840.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Like Harrison, Taylor died in office, and was succeeded by Fillmore.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig Party held its national convention in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, with delegates from every state except for Texas although the Texas Whigs had selected to make the Louisiana delegates their proxies.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, Winfield Scott, Zachary Taylor, and Daniel Webster sought the presidential nomination and Taylor led on every ballot before winning on the fourth ballot.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] After Webster turned down the vice presidential candidacy, Millard Fillmore received the party's vice-presidential nomination on the second ballot after defeating Abbott Lawrence, a Massachusetts politician whose mild opposition to slavery led him to be dubbed a "Cotton Whig".
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] An attempt was made to make both nominations unanimous, but it was unsuccessful due to Taylor's support for the Whig Party being seen as dubious.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party held its national convention in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] There was a credentials dispute over the New York delegation between the Barnburners and Hunkers factions with the Barnburners being anti-slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates voted 126 to 125 to seat both delegations and share their control of New York's votes, but the Barnburners left the convention in disagreement with the compromise while the Hunkers refused to vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The withdrawal of the Barnburners effectively removed former President Martin Van Buren, who had already become unenthusiastic about trying to win the party's nomination after the convention had voted to endorse a platform supporting popular sovereignty, from contention.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] As a result of Van Buren's withdrawal, U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Senator Lewis Cass and Secretary of State James Buchanan were seen as the only serious contenders for the presidential nomination, with a draft effort also focusing on Supreme Court associate justice Levi Woodbury.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] William Orlando Butler won the vice-presidential nomination on the second ballot against John A.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Members of the Whig Party who opposed slavery, New York Barnburners, and members of the Liberty Party met in August 1848 in Buffalo, New York, to found a new political party.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Barnburners made a call for the formation of an anti-slavery party at their conclave in June, and by the People's Convention of Friends of Free Territory, which was organized by Salmon P.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The convention was attended by 165 delegates from eight states to form the Free Soil Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren won the party's presidential nomination against John P.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Hale on the first ballot with 244 votes against Hale's 181 votes.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Hale had been nominated by the Liberty Party in October 1847, but withdrew from the election after the Free Soil Party gave its presidential nomination to Van Buren.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Francis Adams Sr. won the party's vice-presidential nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren knew that the Free Soilers had not the slightest chance of winning, rather that his candidacy would split the Democratic vote and throw the election to the Whigs.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Bitter and aging, Van Buren did not care despite the fact that his life had been built upon the rock of party solidarity and party regularity.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] He loathed Lewis Cass and the principle of popular sovereignty with equal intensity.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Despite their significant showing in the prior presidential election, certain events would conspire to remove the Liberty Party from political significance.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Initially, the party's presidential nomination was to be decided in the fall of 1847 at a Convention in Buffalo, New York.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Hale was nominated for president over Gerrit Smith, brother-in-law to the party's previous presidential nominee James G.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Leicester King, a former judge and state senator in Ohio, was nominated for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-slavery Democrats and Whigs, disappointed with their respective nominees, would form a new movement in conjunction with members of the Liberty Party such as John Hale and Salmon Chase to form the Free Soil Party that summer.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] At this point, both Hale and King withdrew in favor of a Free Soil ticket led by former President Martin Van Buren, and the great majority of members of the Liberty Party followed them into the new political party.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] A small faction refused to support Van Buren for the presidency, however.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] They held another convention in June 1848 as the *"National Liberty Party."* Gerrit Smith was nominated for president with Charles C.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Foote, a Presbyterian minister from Michigan, as his vice presidential running mate.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Native American Party, a precursor to the Know Nothings, which had split from the Whig Party in 1845, met in September 1847 in Philadelphia, where they nominated Zachary Taylor for president and Henry A.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Dearborn of Massachusetts for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] However, when the Whig Party nominated Taylor for the presidency with Millard Fillmore as his running mate the following year, this rendered his previous nomination moot and the Native American Party failed to make an alternate nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Industrial Congress held in Philadelphia on June 13, 1848, nominating Gerrit Smith (nominee of the National Liberty Party) for president, and William S.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] This meeting, inspired by the National Reform Association, was primarily focused on workers rights.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] It established a platform that included planks on land limitation, the reduction of public official's salaries, abolition of the standing army, tariff reduction, and a reduced work week.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was fought without much enthusiasm, and practically without an issue.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Neither of the two great parties made an effort to rally the people to the defense of any important principle.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Whig campaigners, who included future presidents Abraham Lincoln and Rutherford B.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Hayes, talked up Taylor's "antiparty" opposition to the Jacksonian commitment to the spoils system and yellow-dog partisanship.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] In the South, they stressed that he was a Louisiana slaveholder, while in the North they highlighted his Whiggish willingness to defer to Congress on major issues (which he subsequently did not do).
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats repeated, as they had for many years, their opposition to a national bank, high tariffs, and federal subsidies for local improvements.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soilers branded both major parties lackeys of the Slave Power, arguing that the rich planters controlled the agenda of both parties, leaving the ordinary white man out of the picture.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] They had to work around Van Buren's well-known reputation for compromising with slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs had the advantage of highlighting Taylor's military glories.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] With Taylor remaining vague on the issues, the campaign was dominated by personalities and personal attacks, with the Democrats calling Taylor vulgar, uneducated, cruel and greedy, and the Whigs attacking Cass for graft and dishonesty.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The division of the Democrats over slavery allowed Taylor to dominate the Northeast.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soilers were on the ballots in only 17 of the 29 states with the popular vote, making it mathematically possible for Van Buren to win the presidency, but he had no real chance.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Still, the party campaigned vigorously, particularly in the traditional Democratic strongholds in the northeast.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] While some Free Soilers were hopeful of taking enough states to throw the election into the House of Representatives, Van Buren himself knew this was a long shot and that the best that his party could do was lay the groundwork for a hopefully improved showing in 1852.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time in the Second Party System in which the victorious party failed to gain at least a plurality of the counties as well as of the popular vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which Connecticut, Delaware, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Maryland, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, and Rhode Island voted for the Whigs.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the last time that Georgia voted against the Democrats until 1964, the last time Delaware and Louisiana did so until 1872, and the last time Florida and North Carolina did so until 1868.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Discounting Republican Abraham Lincoln's 1864 re-election on the National Union ticket, Taylor is the most recent individual who was not a member of either the Democratic Party or the Republican Party to win a presidential election.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The contest was the first presidential election that took place on the same day in every state, and it was the first time that Election Day was statutorily a Tuesday.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] It is also the first election in which the two candidates that received electoral votes carried the same number of states and the only time that it happened between Democrat and Whig candidates.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] This would only happen again twice, in 1880 and 2020.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] 28.6% of the voting age population and 72.8% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] With Taylor as their candidate, the Whigs won their second and last victory in a presidential election.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor won the electoral college by capturing 163 of the 290 electoral votes.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor out-polled Cass in the popular vote by 138,000 votes, winning 47% of the popular vote, and was elected president.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] A study of the county returns reveals that Free Soil strength drawn at the expense of the major parties differed by region.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] In the East North Central States, it appears at least the majority of the Free Soil strength was drawn from the Whig Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Conversely, in the Middle Atlantic region, Free Soil bases of strength lay in the areas which had hitherto been Democratic, particularly in New York and northern Pennsylvania.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soil Democrats nomination of Van Buren made the victory of Taylor nearly certain in New York.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] On election day, enough Democratic votes were drawn away by Van Buren to give the Whig ticket all but two Democratic counties, thus enabling it to carry hitherto impregnable parts of upper New York state.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats, confronted with an irreparable schism in New York, lost the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] In New England, the Democratic vote declined by 33,000 from its 1844 level, while the Whig vote likewise declined by 15,000 votes.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The third-party vote tripled, and the total vote remained nearly stationary: a partial indication, perhaps, of the derivation of the Free Soil strength in this section.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] For the first time since the existence of the Whig Party, the Whigs failed to gain an absolute majority of the vote in Massachusetts and Vermont.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the Democrats failed to retain their usual majority in Maine; thus only New Hampshire (Democratic) and Rhode Island (Whig) of the states in this section gave their respective victorious parties clear-cut majorities.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Four counties (0.27%) in the West split evenly between Taylor and Cass.
[src:charles-sumner/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The election has sometimes been described as "a contest without an issue," as both major candidates sought to steer clear of divisive subjects.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 2, 1852.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic nominee Franklin Pierce defeated Whig nominee General Winfield Scott.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent Whig President Millard Fillmore had succeeded to the presidency in 1850 upon the death of President Zachary Taylor.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Fillmore endorsed the Compromise of 1850 and enforced the Fugitive Slave Law.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] This earned Fillmore Southern voter support and Northern voter opposition.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] On the 53rd ballot of the sectionally divided 1852 Whig National Convention, Scott defeated Fillmore for the nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats divided among four major candidates at the 1852 Democratic National Convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] On the 49th ballot, dark horse candidate Franklin Pierce won nomination by consensus compromise.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soil Party, a third party opposed to the extension of slavery in the United States and into the territories, nominated New Hampshire Senator John P.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] With few policy differences between the two major candidates, the election became a personality contest.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Though Scott had commanded in the Mexican–American War, Pierce also served.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Scott strained Whig Party unity as his anti-slavery reputation gravely damaged his campaign in the South.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Southern Whigs and a separate group of Southern Democrats each nominated insurgent tickets, but both efforts failed to attract support.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] King won a comfortable popular majority, carrying 27 of the 31 states.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Pierce won the highest share of the electoral vote since James Monroe's uncontested 1820 re-election.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soil Party regressed to less than five percent of the national popular vote, down from more than ten percent in 1848, while overwhelming defeat and disagreement about slavery soon drove the Whig Party to disintegrate.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-slavery Whigs and Free Soilers would ultimately coalesce into the new Republican Party, which would quickly become a formidable movement in the free states.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Not until 1876 would Democrats again win a majority of the popular vote for president, and not until 1932 would they win a majority in both the popular vote and the electoral college.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party held its national convention in Baltimore, Maryland, in June 1852.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Hallett, the chair of the Democratic National Committee, limited the sizes of the delegations to their electoral votes and a vote to maintain the two-thirds requirement for the presidential and vice-presidential nomination was passed by a vote of 269 to 13.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Douglas were the main candidates for the nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] All of the candidates led the ballot for the presidential nomination at one point, but all of them failed to meet the two-thirds requirement.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Franklin Pierce was put up for the nomination by the Virginia delegation.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Pierce won the nomination when the delegates switched their support to him after he had received the unanimous support of the delegates from New England.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] He won on the second day of balloting after forty-nine ballots.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The delegation from Maine proposed that the vice-presidential nomination should be given to somebody from the Southern United States with William R.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] King led on the first ballot before winning on the second ballot.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig Party held its national convention in Baltimore, Maryland, in June 1852.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The call for the convention had been made by Whig members of the United States Congress and thirty-one states were represented.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A vote to have each state's vote be based on its electoral college strength was passed by a vote of 149 to 144, but it was rescinded due to disagreements from the Southern states and smaller Northern states.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party had been divided by the Compromise of 1850 and was divided over the presidential nomination between incumbent president Millard Fillmore, who received support from the South, and Winfield Scott, who received his support from the North.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Seward, who had been the main opponent of the compromise in the United States Senate and advised President Zachary Taylor against it, supported Scott.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Fillmore offered to give his delegates to Daniel Webster if he received the support of forty-one delegates on his own, but Webster was unsuccessful.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Scott won the nomination on the 53rd ballot.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] William Alexander Graham won the vice-presidential nomination without a formal vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Nine southern Whig members of Congress, including Alexander H.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Stephens and Robert Toombs, refused to support Scott.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soil Party was still the strongest third party in 1852.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] However, following the Compromise of 1850, most of the "Barnburners" who supported it in 1848 had returned to the Democratic Party while most of the Conscience Whigs rejoined the Whig Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The second Free Soil National Convention assembled in the Masonic Hall in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Hale was nominated for president with 192 delegate votes (sixteen votes were cast for a smattering of candidates).
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Julian of Indiana was nominated for vice president over Samuel Lewis of Ohio and Joshua R.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A movement among disaffected Whigs to nominate Daniel Webster began in earnest following the Whig National Convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] As Webster made his way from Washington to his farm in Franklin, New Hampshire, many Whigs expressed their continued loyalty to him; some spoke of forming a new "Union" party with Webster as its presidential candidate.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Webster received letters pressuring him to endorse the new party movement, hoping he'd allow his name to be used by an opposition convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In Boston, the Webster movement was led by those who had opposed Scott's nomination, most notably George Ticknor Curtis, who had served controversially as a federal fugitive slave commissioner.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] These men had grown tired of military chieftains at the top of the Whig ticket and argued that the party had fallen under the control of dangerous foes of the Compromise.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They lacked political experience and had little to lose.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] When Webster reached Boston, the city held a huge celebration in his honor, which was "by far the most impressive and touching demonstration ever made by that people toward Mr.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Those who had stuck with Webster throughout the nomination season knew that an independent bid was hopeless.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They feared that his candidacy would damage the Whig Party and tarnish his legacy as the great "Defender of the Constitution." Although opposed to his nomination, Webster met Curtis in Marshfield and told him that he could not prevent anyone from voting for him.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Privately, he was convinced that the Whig Party was disintegrating and that endorsing its ticket would be both futile and demeaning.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, he held a favorable view of Pierce and advised his assistant, Charles Lanman, along with Peter Harvey, to vote for him.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Webster would never publicly comment on the nomination movement, which at this point had spread to New York and would shortly receive the endorsement of one faction of the Georgia Constitutional Union Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, a group of pro-Webster Whigs nominated electors pledged to Webster and Graham, the Whig nominee for vice president, prompting Graham to disavow the Webster movement.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, encouraged by the actions of the Georgia Union Whigs, Curtis and his followers held a convention at Faneuil Hall in Boston on September 15 and endorsed the nominations made by the Georgia Unionist convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] However, in early September, Webster's health seriously declined.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] During his final days, his friends attempted to persuade him to denounce the independent movement.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They abandoned their efforts after Abbot, who had initially favored a formal statement of party loyalty, concluded that it was unfair for them to pressure a dying man who had lost all interest in politics.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Considering it useless to trouble him further, Curtis, on October 21, ordered the Webster Executive Committee in Boston to suspend activities.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Webster died nine days before the election of a cerebral hemorrhage on October 24, 1852.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitutional Union Party was a political party organized in several slave states to support the Compromise of 1850.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It was one of two major parties in the state of Georgia in the early 1850s, alongside the Southern Rights Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party formed as a merger of the local Democratic and Whig unionists.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] While former Whigs in the party were given important positions, such as senate seats, the party's executive committee was made up of mostly Democrats.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Following the acquiescence of the Southern Rights leaders to the Compromise after 1851, the need for a dedicated Union party diminished.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] With a supermajority in the state legislature, the Union Party began its program of division of the political spoils, which eventually led to a split between the Democratic and Whig factions.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Party leaders adopted a wait-and-see attitude as the presidential election approached.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In April, Union Democrats held a state convention that nominated delegates to attend the Democratic National Convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Union Whigs held their own convention later that summer and appointed a delegation led by William C.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Dawson to attend the Whig National Convention, instructing them to support the nomination of Millard Fillmore.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] These separate conventions laid the groundwork for the party's eventual collapse, providing Union Democrats with an excuse to return to the Democratic fold.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Although the Union Democrats supported Pierce as the national Democratic nominee, they refused to support the state Pierce ticket nominated by the Southern Rights Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, they ran their own ticket with the tacit consent of Governor Howell Cobb.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] At the subsequent Constitutional Union state convention on July 15, the Union Democrats were able to nominate an electoral ticket pledged to Pierce, causing Union Whigs to walk out of the convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Fearing that Scott would repudiate the Compromise, they nominated Webster in a convention at Macon with Charles J.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Jenkins as the candidate for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Pro-Scott Whigs held a concurrent convention in Macon, but a fusion of the two groups failed to occur.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Following these conventions, the Democratic majority on the Constitutional Union Party's executive committee declared the party dissolved and withdrew the independent Pierce ticket.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Around the mid-1830s, nativists were present in New York politics, under the aegis of the American Republican Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The American Republican party was formed in 1843 in major opposition to Catholicism and Catholic immigrants.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In 1845, the party changed its name to the Native American Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Their opponents nicknamed them the "Know Nothings".
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party liked the name, and it became the official nickname of the party until it collapsed in 1860.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In 1852, the original presidential nominee planned by the Native American Party was Daniel Webster, the presidential nominee of the Union Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They nominated Webster without his permission, with George C.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Washington (grandnephew of George Washington) as his vice presidential running mate.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Webster died of natural causes nine days before the election, and the Know-Nothings quickly replaced Webster by nominating Jacob Broom for president and replaced Washington with Reynell Coates for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Southern Rights Party was a political party organized in several slave states to oppose the Compromise of 1850, viewing it as inadequate protection for the South, and advocate for secession from the Union, though it later abandoned serious plans for secession.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It was one of two major parties in the states of Alabama, Georgia, and Mississippi in the early 1850s, alongside the Union Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party was made up of mostly Democrats and State Rights Whigs.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] By 1851, most Southern Rights Democrats had acquiesced to the compromise, believing further opposition to it was hopeless.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It was unclear in early 1852 if the remnants of the party would contest the presidential election.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] When the Southern Rights Convention of Alabama in Montgomery was held in early March, only six counties were represented.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The convention voted to keep the party alive throughout the southern states to oppose both the Democrats and Whigs, or cooperate with either based on the extent to which their doctrines aligned with the principles of the Southern Rights men.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the party was too disorganized to nominate its own candidate and have an effect on the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The South Carolinian *Southern Standard* argued that the Southern Rights parties should coordinate and attempt to influence the Democratic nomination, though not by joining the Democratic convention, as that might obligate them to support an unfavorable candidate.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the paper proposed holding a parallel convention at the same time and place, so they could be "prepared to act as circumstances might require".
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] After the Democratic National Convention, the party was not sure that it wanted to support Franklin Pierce and William R.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Another Southern Rights Convention was held in Montgomery from July 13–15 and debated at length whether to keep up a separate organization and whether they wanted to nominate Pierce.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The convention was unable to arrive at a decision, deciding to appoint a committee to review the positions of Scott/Graham and Pierce/King, with the option of calling a "national" convention if the two major-party tickets appeared deficient.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The committee took its time reviewing the positions of Pierce and Scott, finally deciding on August 25 to call a convention for a Southern Rights Party ticket.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Pierce had failed to answer their inquiry and on August 27 it was reported that Scort replied to the letter of the Alabama Southern Rights Central Committee, but declined giving specitic answers to their interrogatories.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The convention assembled in Montgomery, Alabama, with 62 delegates present, a committee to recommend a ticket being appointed while the delegates listened to speeches in the interim.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The committee eventually recommended former senator George Troup of Georgia for president, and former governor John Quitman of Mississippi for vice president; they were unanimously nominated.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The two nominees accepted their nominations soon after the convention, which was held rather late in the season.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Troup stated in a letter, dated September 27 and printed in the New York Times on October 16, that he had planned to vote for Pierce/King and had always wholeheartedly supported William R.D.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] He indicated in the letter that he preferred to decline the honor, as he was rather ill at the time and feared that he would die before the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The state party's executive committee edited the letter to excise those portions which indicated that Troup preferred to decline, a fact which was revealed after the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Seeking to gain favor of the successful national party, whom would most likely be the Democrats, the Resistance Party, as the Georgian branch was known, changed its name to the Southern Rights Party and held a convention on March 31, 1852.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] At this convention, it nominated delegates to the national Democratic convention and an electoral ticket headed by Herschel V.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] These men were instructed to show no preference for any particular candidate, although a large majority of the convention that nominated them supported Buchanan as their first choice.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In April, the Democrats in the Constitutional Union Party had held a convention where they nominated delegates to the national Democratic convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Following the dissolution of the Constitutional Union Party, Georgia Democrats and the Southern Rights Party met in a joint convention and attempted to consolidate support for Pierce in a combined Southern Rights-Democratic ticket.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Liberty Party had ceased to become a significant political force after most of its members joined the Free Soil Party in 1848.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, some of those who rejected the fusion strategy held a Liberty Party National Convention in Buffalo, New York.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] There were few delegates present, so a ticket was recommended and a later convention called.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Convention recommended Gerrit Smith of New York for president and Charles Durkee of Wisconsin for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A second convention was held in Syracuse, New York, in early September 1852, but it too failed to draw enough delegates to select nominees.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Yet a third convention gathered in Syracuse later that month and nominated William Goodell of New York for president and S.M.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A slate of electors nominated by the Liberty Party received 72 votes in New York.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs' platform was almost indistinguishable from that of the Democrats, reducing the campaign to a contest between the personalities of the two candidates.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The lack of clearcut issues between the two parties helped drive voter turnout down to its lowest level since 1836.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The decline was further exacerbated by Scott's antislavery reputation, which decimated the Southern Whig vote at the same time as the pro-slavery Whig platform undermined the Northern Whig vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] After the Compromise of 1850 was passed, many of the southern Whig Party members broke with the party's key figure, Henry Clay.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Finally, Scott's status as a war hero was somewhat offset by the fact that Pierce was himself a Mexican–American War brigadier general.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats adopted the slogan: *The Whigs we Polked in forty-four, We'll Pierce in fifty-two*, playing on the names of Pierce and former president James K.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Just nine days before the election, Webster died, causing many Union state parties to remove their slates of electors.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Union ticket appeared on the ballot in Georgia and Massachusetts, however.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] 27.3% of the voting age population and 69.5% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The fact that Daniel Webster received a substantial share of the vote in Georgia and Massachusetts, even though he was dead, shows how disenchanted voters were with the two main candidates.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] As a result of the devastating defeat and the growing tensions within the party between pro-slavery Southerners and anti-slavery Northerners, the Whig Party quickly fell apart after the 1852 election and ceased to exist.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Some Southern Whigs would join the Democratic Party, and many Northern Whigs would help to form the new Republican Party in 1854.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Some Whigs in both sections would support the so-called "Know-Nothing" party in the 1856 presidential election.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Similarly, the Free Soil Party rapidly fell away into obscurity after the election, and the remaining members mostly opted to join the former Northern Whigs in forming the Republican Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Southern Rights Party effectively collapsed following the election, attaining only five percent of the vote in Alabama, and a few hundred in its nominee's home state of Georgia.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It would elect a number of Congressmen in 1853, but they would rejoin the Democratic Party upon taking their seats in Congress.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Kentucky and Tennessee were the only slave states that Scott won.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] None of the future Confederate states elected governors in the 1852 and 1853 gubernatorial elections, and the Whigs only won 14 of the South's 65 seats in the U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party held no state legislatures in the South except in Tennessee.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats, who carried all but two northern states, would see a decline in the north following the 1854 elections due to controversy around the Kansas–Nebraska Act.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They lost control of all free state legislatures except for two, and their seats in the U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] House from the north fell from 93 to 23.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The four elections from 1840 to 1852 saw the incumbent party defeated each time; the only other such streak was from 1884 to 1896.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It was, however, the last election in which the Democrats' chief opponent won Kentucky until 1896, and the last until 1928 in which the Democrats' opponent obtained an absolute majority in Kentucky.
[src:charles-sumner/1852-united-states-presidential-election] *United States Presidential Elections, 1788–1860* pp 115-134 with differences with Walter Dean Burnham, *Presidential ballots, 1836–1892* (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1955) pp 247–57 noted.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The **1856 Republican National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention that met from June 17 to June 19, 1856, at Musical Fund Hall at 808 Locust Street in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] It was the first national nominating convention of the Republican Party, founded two years earlier in 1854.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] It was held to nominate the party's candidates for president and vice president in the 1856 election.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont, a former United States Senator from California, for president, and former Senator William L.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Dayton of New Jersey for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The convention also appointed members of the newly established Republican National Committee.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The Republican Party had been organized by opponents of the expansion of slavery in the territories following the passage of the 1854 Kansas–Nebraska Act.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Chase, and Charles Sumner all taking their names out of consideration, Frémont entered the Republican convention as the front-runner for the presidential nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont had previously been nominated by the North American Party, which consisted of anti-slavery members of the American Party who were unwilling to support the American Party candidate, Millard Fillmore.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Though Associate Justice John McLean of Ohio had the backing of some delegates, Frémont clinched the presidential nomination on the first formal ballot of the Republican convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Dayton was nominated on the first formal vice-presidential ballot, defeating former Congressman Abraham Lincoln of Illinois and several other candidates.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The Republican ticket carried several Northern states in the general election, but the Democratic ticket of James Buchanan and John C.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] On June 19, 1855, a small gathering of like-minded individuals met in Washington, D.C. where they passed a resolution noting the recent abrogation of "all compromises, real or imaginary" by the opening of Kansas Territory and Nebraska Territory to the possible institution of slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The 22-member Republican National Committee, which included one representative from each state attending the Pittsburgh Convention, met in plenary session on March 27, 1856, at the Willard Hotel in Washington, D.C., and issued a call for a formal presidential nominating convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] This was slated to begin on June 17, 1856, in Philadelphia.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Each state organization was to be allocated six at-large delegates, plus three delegates for each congressional district.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The candidates to be nominated by the new Republican party were first nominated by the anti-slavery rump of the American Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] American party members from the North who were opposed to slavery formed their own party after the nomination of former President Millard Fillmore in Philadelphia.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] This party called for its national convention to be held in New York, New York, just before the Republican National Convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Party leaders hoped to nominate a joint ticket with the Republicans to defeat Buchanan.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The national convention was held on June 12 to 20, 1856 in New York.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont was the favorite to attain the Republican nomination there was a considerable desire for the North American party to nominate him, but it was feared that in doing so they may possibly injure his chances to actually become the Republican nominee.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The delegates voted repeatedly on a nominee for president without a result.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Banks was nominated for president on the 10th ballot over John C.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont and John McLean, with the understanding that he would withdraw from the race and endorse John C.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont once he had won the Republican nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The delegates, preparing to return home, unanimously nominated Frémont on the 11th ballot shortly after his nomination by the Republican Party in Philadelphia.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The chairman of the convention, William F.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Johnston, had been nominated to run for vice-president, but later withdrew when the North Americans and the Republicans failed to find an acceptable accommodation between him and the Republican nominee, William Dayton.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The first Republican National Convention was held in the Musical Fund Hall in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on June 17–19, 1856.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] It was led by Robert Emmet as temporary chairman and Henry S.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The convention approved an anti-slavery platform that called for congressional sovereignty in the territories, an end to polygamy in Mormon settlements, and federal assistance for a transcontinental railroad.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Kentucky was the only southern state to have a delegation at the convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont, John McLean, Nathaniel Banks, William Seward, Salmon Chase, and Charles Sumner all were considered by those at the convention, but the latter three requested that their names be withdrawn.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] The Massachusetts delegation resolved in a morning meeting to vote unanimously for Banks.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] However, the name of Banks was then authoritatively and peremptorily withdrawn and the delegation resolved as a unit to support Frémont.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] McLean's name was initially withdrawn by his manager Rufus Spalding, but the withdrawal was rescinded at the strong behest of the Pennsylvania delegation led by Thaddeus Stevens.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Frémont was nominated for president overwhelmingly on the formal ballot.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-republican-national-convention] Dayton was nominated for vice president over Abraham Lincoln.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 4, 1856.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic nominee James Buchanan defeated Republican nominee John C.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont and Know Nothing/Whig nominee Millard Fillmore.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The main issue was the expansion of slavery as facilitated by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Buchanan defeated President Franklin Pierce at the 1856 Democratic National Convention for the nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Slavery was the main issue, and with it the question of the survival of the United States as it then existed.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats were seen as the pro-slavery party.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] While the new Republican party was hostile to slavery, they limited their efforts to the politically more manageable question of the extension of slavery into federal territories (and its removal from the District of Columbia).
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The nativist Know Nothings (known formally as the American Party) competed with the Republicans to replace the moribund Whig Party as the primary opposition to the Democrats.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] They emphasized opposition to Catholic immigrants.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The 1856 Republican National Convention nominated a ticket led by Frémont, an explorer and military officer who had served in the Mexican–American War.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Know Nothings, who ignored slavery and instead emphasized anti-immigration and anti-Catholic policies, nominated a ticket led by former Whig President Millard Fillmore.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Domestic political turmoil was a major factor in the nominations of both Buchanan and Fillmore, who appealed in part because of their recent time abroad, when they did not have to take a position on the divisive questions related to slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats supported expansionist slave-holding policies generally of varying intensities.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Southern Democrats were all in favor of the expansion of slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Some wanted to obtain Cuba as slave territory, as espoused by the Ostend Manifesto.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Northern Democrats called for "popular sovereignty", which in theory would allow the residents in a territory to decide for themselves the legal status of slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] In practice, in Kansas Territory, it produced a state-level civil war.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont opposed the expansion of slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Buchanan called that position "extremist", warning that a Republican victory would lead to disunion, a then constant issue of political debate which had already been long discussed and advocated.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Know Nothings attempted to present themselves as the one party capable of bridging the sectional divides.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] All three major parties found support in the North, but the Republicans had virtually no backing in the South.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Buchanan won a plurality of the popular vote and a majority of the electoral vote, taking all but one slave state and five free states.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont won a majority of electoral votes from free states and finished second in the nationwide popular vote, while Fillmore took 21.5% of the popular vote but only carried Maryland.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Know Nothings soon collapsed as a national party, as most of its anti-slavery members joined the Republican Party after the 1857 *Dred Scott v.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] This election marked the end of the Second Party System and also proved to be the last Democratic presidential victory until 1884, as Republicans emerged as the dominant party during and after the Civil War.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The 1856 presidential election was primarily waged among three political parties, though other parties had been active in the spring of the year.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The conventions of these parties are considered below in order of the party's popular vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party was wounded from its devastating losses in the 1854–1855 midterm elections.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Douglas of Illinois, who had sponsored the Kansas-Nebraska Act, entered the race in opposition to President Franklin Pierce.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Pennsylvania delegation continued to sponsor its favorite son Buchanan.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Seventh Democratic National Convention was held in Smith and Nixon's Hall in Cincinnati, Ohio, on June 2 to 6, 1856.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates were deeply divided over slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] On the first ballot, Buchanan placed first with 135.5 votes to 122.5 for Pierce, 33 for Douglas, and 5 for Senator Lewis Cass, who had been the presidential nominee in 1848.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] With each succeeding ballot, Buchanan gradually extended his lead, while Douglas began making significant gains at Pierce's expense.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] By the end of the first day, with 14 ballots having been completed, it was clear that Pierce would not be nominated for a second term, and he withdrew his name from contention.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] For the first time in American history someone who had been elected president was denied re-nomination after seeking it.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] A host of candidates were nominated for the vice presidency, but a number of them attempted to withdraw themselves from consideration, among them the eventual nominee, John C.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge, besides having been selected as an elector, was also supporting former Speaker of the House Linn Boyd for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] However, following a draft effort led by the delegation from Vermont, Breckinridge was nominated on the second ballot.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican Party was formed in early 1854 to oppose the Kansas-Nebraska Act.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] During the midterm elections of 1854–1855, the Republican Party was one of the patchwork of anti-administration parties contesting the election, but they were able to win thirteen seats in the House of Representatives for the 34th Congress.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] However, the party collaborated with other disaffected groups and gradually absorbed them.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] In the elections of 1855, the Republican Party won three governorships.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The first Republican National Convention was held in the Musical Fund Hall in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on June 17 to 19, 1856.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The convention approved an anti-slavery platform that called for congressional sovereignty in the territories, an end to polygamy in Mormon settlements, and federal assistance for a transcontinental railroad—a political outcome of the Pacific Railroad Surveys.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont, John McLean, William Seward, Salmon Chase, and Charles Sumner all were considered by those at the convention, but the latter three requested that their names be withdrawn.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Seward and Chase did not feel that the party was yet sufficiently organized to have a realistic chance of taking the White House and were content to wait until the next election.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Sumner was in no fit condition to run after being violently assaulted on the Senate floor a month before the convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont was nominated for president overwhelmingly on the formal ballot, and William L.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The American Party, formerly the Native American Party, was the vehicle of the Know Nothing movement.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The American Party absorbed most of the former Whig Party that had not gone to either the Republicans or Democrats in 1854, and by 1855 it had established itself as the chief opposition party to the Democrats.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] In the 82 races for the House of Representatives in 1854, the American Party ran 76 candidates, 35 of whom won.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] None of the six independents or Whigs who ran in these races were elected.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The party gained control over the state governments of California, Connecticut, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Rhode Island in the 1854 and 1855 elections.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The party also controlled the Tennessee legislature and received at least 45% of the vote in multiple Southern states, far better than the Whig Party following 1848.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The party then succeeded in electing Nathaniel P.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Banks as Speaker of the House in the 34th Congress.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] However, the party started to break apart at sectional lines over slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Wilson led Northern delegates out of the party's 1855 national council in Philadelphia in protest of it adopting a plank endorsing the Kansas-Nebraska Act.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] 70 Northern delegates left the 1856 convention to create the North American Party after a resolution calling for the Kansas-Nebraska Act to be repealed was defeated.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The American National Convention was held in National Hall in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on February 22 to 25, 1856.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Following the decision by party leaders in 1855 not to press the slavery issue, the convention had to decide how to deal with the Ohio chapter of the party, which was vocally anti-slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The convention closed the Ohio chapter and re-opened it under more moderate leadership.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Delegates from New England, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Illinois, Iowa, and other Northern states bolted when a resolution that would have required all prospective nominees to be in favor of prohibiting slavery north of the 36'30' parallel was voted down.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] This removed a greater part of the American Party's support in the North outside of New York, where the conservative faction of the Whig Party remained faithful.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] While Banks was the early favorite for the party's presidential nomination, he publicly declined the nomination and effectively broke from the Know-Nothings, though he would not formally defect to the Republican Party until after the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] After Banks removed himself from consideration, the only name with much support was former President Millard Fillmore.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Historian Allan Nevins says that Fillmore was not a Know-Nothing or a nativist.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] He was out of the country when the presidential nomination came and had not been consulted about running.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Furthermore, Fillmore was neither a member of the party nor had he ever attended an American [Know-Nothing] gathering, nor had he by "spoken or written word [...] indicated a subscription to American tenets".
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Fillmore was nominated with 179 votes out of the 234 votes cast.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The convention chose Andrew Jackson Donelson of Tennessee for vice president with 181 votes to 30 scattered votes and 24 abstentions.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Although the nativist argument of the American Party had considerable success in local and state elections in 1854–55, Fillmore in 1856 concentrated almost entirely on national unity.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Historian Tyler Anbinder says, "The American party had dropped nativism from its agenda." Fillmore won 22% of the national popular vote.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The anti-slavery "Americans" from the North formed their own party after the nomination of Fillmore in Philadelphia.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] This party called for its national convention to be held in New York City, just before the Republican National Convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont was the favorite to attain the Republican presidential nomination there was a considerable desire for the North American party to nominate him, but it was feared that in doing so they may possibly injure his chances to actually become the Republican presidential nominee.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont once he had won the Republican presidential nomination.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Johnston, had been nominated to run for vice president, but later withdrew when the North Americans and the Republicans failed to find an acceptable accommodation between him and the Republican vice presidential nominee, William Dayton.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] A group of North American delegates called the North American Seceders withdrew from the North American Party's convention and met separately.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] They objected to the attempt to work with the Republican Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Seceders held their own national convention on June 16 and 17, 1856.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] 19 delegates unanimously nominated Robert F.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Stockton for president and Kenneth Rayner for vice president.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Seceders' ticket later withdrew from the contest, with Stockton endorsing Millard Fillmore for the presidency.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig Party was reeling from electoral losses since 1852.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Half of its leaders in the South bolted to the Southern Democratic Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] In the North the Whig Party was moribund with most of its anti-slavery members joining the Republican Party.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] This party remained somewhat alive in states like New York and Pennsylvania by joining the anti-slavery movement.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The fifth (and last) Whig National Convention was held in the Hall of the Maryland Institute in Baltimore, Maryland, on September 17 and 18, 1856.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] There were 150 delegates sent from 26 states.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Though the leaders of this party wanted to keep the Whig Party alive, it became irretrievably doomed once these 150 Whig delegates decided unanimously to endorse the American Party's national ticket of Fillmore and Donelson.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] By 1856, very little of the Liberty Party remained.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Most of its members joined the Free Soil Party in 1848 and nearly of all what remained of the party joined the Republicans in 1854.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] None of the three candidates did any public campaigning.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican Party opposed the extension of slavery into the territories: in fact, its slogan was "Free speech, free press, free soil, free men, Frémont and victory!" The Republicans thus crusaded against the Slave Power, warning it was destroying republican values.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats warned that a Republican victory would bring a civil war.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican platform opposed the repeal of the Missouri Compromise through the Kansas–Nebraska Act, which enacted the policy of popular sovereignty, allowing settlers to decide whether a new state would enter the Union as free or slave.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Republicans also accused the Pierce administration of allowing a fraudulent territorial government to be imposed upon the citizens of the Kansas Territory, thus engendering the violence that had raged in Bleeding Kansas.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] They advocated the immediate admittance of Kansas as a free state.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Along with opposing the spread of slavery into the continental territories of the United States, the party also opposed the Ostend Manifesto, which advocated the annexation of Cuba from Spain.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] In sum, the campaign's true focus was against the system of slavery, which they felt was destroying the republican values that the Union had been founded upon.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic platform supported the Kansas-Nebraska Act and popular sovereignty.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The party supported the pro-slavery territorial legislature elected in Kansas, opposed the free-state elements within Kansas, and castigated the Topeka Constitution as an illegal document written during an illegal convention.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats also supported the plan to annex Cuba, advocated in the Ostend Manifesto, which Buchanan helped devise while serving as minister to Britain.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The most influential aspect of the Democratic campaign was a warning that a Republican victory would lead to the secession of numerous southern states.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The main Democratic campaign was a counter-crusade against the Republicans.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] They ridiculed Frémont's military record and warned that his victory would bring civil war.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Because Fillmore was considered by many incapable of securing the presidency on the American ticket, Whigs were urged to support Buchanan.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats also called on nativists to make common cause with them against the specter of sectionalism even if they had once attacked their political views.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Fillmore and the Americans, meanwhile, insisted that they were the only "national party" since the Democrats leaning in favor of the South and the Republicans were fanatically in favor of Northern fanaticism.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] A minor scandal erupted when the Americans, seeking to turn the national dialogue back in the direction of nativism, put out a false rumor that Frémont was in fact a Roman Catholic.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Because of the Republican candidate's French-Canadian ancestry and surname, many voters accepted the allegation at face value.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats ran with it, and the Republicans found themselves unable to counteract the rumor effectively given that while the statements were false, any stern message against those assertions might have crippled their efforts to attain the votes of German Catholics.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Attempts were made to refute it through friends and colleagues, but the issue persisted throughout the campaign and might have cost Frémont the support of a number of American Party members.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] 30.6% of the voting age population and 79.4% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign had a different nature in the free states and the slave states.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] In the free states, there was a three-way campaign, which Frémont won with 45.2% of the vote to 41.5% for Buchanan and 13.3% for Fillmore; Frémont received 114 electoral votes to 62 for Buchanan.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] In the slave states, however, the contest was for all intents and purposes between Buchanan and Fillmore; Buchanan won 56.1% of the vote to 43.8% for Fillmore and 0.1% for Frémont, receiving 112 electoral votes to 8 for Fillmore.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Nationwide, Buchanan won 174 electoral votes, a majority, and was thus elected.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont received no votes in ten of the fourteen slave states with a popular vote; he obtained 306 in Delaware, 285 in Maryland, 283 in Virginia, and 314 in Kentucky.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] One county (0.06%), in Georgia, was split evenly between Buchanan and Fillmore.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] This would be the only presidential election where the Know-Nothing Party put up a campaign, as the party began to splinter.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] After the Supreme Court's controversial *Dred Scott v.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Sandford* ruling in 1857, most of the anti-slavery members of the party joined the Republicans.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The pro-slavery wing of the American Party remained strong on the local and state levels in a few Southern states, but, by the 1860 election, they no longer were a serious national political movement.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Most of their remaining members either joined or supported the Constitutional Union Party in 1860.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which a candidate won without any electoral votes from New England until 2004, and only the second such occurrence after Democrat Andrew Jackson in 1828, and the only time that a Republican swept the region without winning the presidency.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] It is also the most recent election in which a Democrat was elected to succeed a Democratic president, and is only the second instance of such an occurrence, the first being in 1836.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] This also started the long Republican trend in Vermont, which would not be broken until 1964, over a century later.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Gasconade County, Missouri, as of the 2024 United States presidential election, has not voted Democratic since, marking the beginning of the longest active voting streak for any party at the county level.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] Source: Data from Walter Dean Burnham, *Presidential ballots, 1836–1892* (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1955) pp 247–57.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] During the joint session of Congress to count the electoral votes, a dispute occurred over Wisconsin's slate.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] The electors of Wisconsin, delayed by a snowstorm, did not cast their votes for Frémont and Dayton until several days after the appointed time and sent a certificate mentioning this fact.
[src:charles-sumner/1856-united-states-presidential-election] When the votes for the state were opened by acting Vice President James Mason, he counted them over the objections of the leadership of both Houses of Congress.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner chaired the Senate Foreign Relations Committee from 1861 to 1871, until he lost the position following a dispute with President Ulysses S.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Grant over the attempted annexation of Santo Domingo.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After breaking with Grant, he joined the Liberal Republican Party, spending his final two years in the Senate alienated from his party.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner began his political activism as a member of various anti-slavery groups, leading to his election to the U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Senate in 1851 as a member of the Free Soil Party; he soon became a founding member of the Republican Party.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In the Senate, he devoted his efforts to opposing the "Slave Power," which in 1856 culminated in a vicious beating, almost to death, by Representative Preston Brooks on the Senate floor.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner's severe injuries and extended absence from the Senate made him a symbol of the anti-slavery cause.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Though he did not return to the Senate until 1859, Massachusetts reelected him in 1857, leaving his empty desk as a reminder of the incident, which polarized the nation as the Civil War approached.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] During the war, Sumner led the Radical Republican faction, which believed President Abraham Lincoln was too moderate toward the South.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] As chair of the Foreign Relations Committee, Sumner worked to ensure that the United Kingdom and France did not intervene on behalf of the Confederate States.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After the Union won the war and Lincoln was assassinated, Sumner and Thaddeus Stevens led congressional efforts to grant equal civil and voting rights to freedmen and to block ex-Confederates from power so they would not reverse the gains derived from the Union's victory in the war.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] President Andrew Johnson's persistent opposition to these efforts played a role in his impeachment in 1868.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] During the Grant administration, Sumner fell out of favor with his party.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He supported the annexation of Alaska but opposed Grant's proposal to annex Santo Domingo.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After leading senators to defeat the Santo Domingo Treaty in 1870, Sumner denounced Grant in terms that made reconciliation impossible, and Senate Republicans stripped Sumner of his power.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner opposed Grant's 1872 reelection and supported Liberal Republican Horace Greeley.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner died in office less than two years later.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Charles Sumner was born at 58 Irving Street in Boston on January 6, 1811.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His father, Charles Pinckney Sumner, was a Harvard-educated lawyer, abolitionist, and early proponent of racial integration of schools, who shocked 19th-century Boston by opposing anti-miscegenation laws.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His mother, Relief Jacob, worked as a seamstress before marrying Charles.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Both of Sumner's parents were born in poverty and were described as exceedingly formal and undemonstrative.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His father served as Clerk of the Massachusetts House of Representatives from 1806 to 1807 and from 1810 to 1811, and he had a moderately successful legal practice.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Throughout Sumner's childhood, his family teetered on the edge of the middle class while living in a majority Black part of the Beacon Hill neighborhood.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Growing up around Black Bostonians, who often shared stories of injustice they faced, would shape Sumner's future politics, helping spur his fight for racial equality.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Charles Pinckney Sumner hated slavery and told his son that freeing the slaves would "do us no good" unless society treated them equally.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He was a close associate of Unitarian leader William Ellery Channing.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Expanding on Channing's argument that human beings had infinite potential to improve themselves, Sumner concluded that environment had "an important, if not controlling influence" in shaping people.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The family's fortunes improved in 1825, when Charles Pinckney Sumner became Sheriff of Suffolk County; he held the position until his death in 1838.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The family attended Trinity Church, but after 1825, they occupied a pew in King's Chapel.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner's father was also able to provide higher education for his children; the young Charles attended Boston Latin School, where he befriended Robert Charles Winthrop, James Freeman Clarke, Samuel Francis Smith, and Wendell Phillips.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1830, he graduated from Harvard College, where he lived in Hollis Hall and was a member of the Porcellian Club.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He then attended Harvard Law School, where he became a protégé of Unitarian Joseph Story and an enthusiastic student of jurisprudence.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After graduating in 1834, Sumner was admitted to the bar and entered private practice in Boston in partnership with George Stillman Hillard.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] A visit to Washington decided him against a political career, and he returned to Boston resolved to practice law.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He contributed to the quarterly *American Jurist* and edited Story's court decisions as well as some law texts.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] From 1836 to 1837, Sumner lectured at Harvard Law School.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1837, Sumner visited Europe with financial support from benefactors, including Story and Congressman Richard Fletcher.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He landed at Le Havre and found the cathedral at Rouen striking: "The great lion of the north of France ... transcending all that my imagination had pictured." He reached Paris in December, studied French, and visited the Louvre.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He mastered French within six months and attended lectures at the Sorbonne on subjects ranging from geology to Greek history to criminal law.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner decided that Americans' predisposition to see blacks as inferior was a learned viewpoint, and he determined to become an abolitionist upon returning to America.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Over the next three years, Sumner became fluent in Spanish, German, and Italian, and met with many leading European statesmen.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1838, he visited Britain, where Lord Brougham declared that he "had never met with any man of Sumner's age of such extensive legal knowledge and natural legal intellect".
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Though he often praised British society as more refined than American, Sumner published a fierce defense of the American position in the dispute over the Maine-Canada boundary, circulated by Minister to France Lewis Cass.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1840, at age 29, Sumner returned to Boston to practice law but devoted more time to lecturing at Harvard Law, editing court reports, and contributing to law journals, especially on historical and biographical themes.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner developed friendships with several prominent Bostonians, particularly Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, whose house he visited regularly starting in the 1840s.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Longfellow's daughters found his stateliness amusing; he would ceremoniously open doors for the children while saying "*In presequas*" ("after you") in a sonorous tone.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1840 he became an hereditary member of the Massachusetts Society of the Cincinnati in succession to his father.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner embarked on a public political career in 1845, when he emerged as one of the most prominent critics of slavery in the city of Boston and the state of Massachusetts, a hotbed of abolitionist sentiment.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On July 4, Sumner delivered the Boston Independence Day oration, *The True Grandeur of Nations*.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His speech was critical of the move toward war with Mexico and an impassioned appeal for freedom and peace.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner considered the conflict a war of aggression but was primarily concerned that captured territories would expand slavery westward.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He soon became a sought-after orator for formal occasions throughout Boston.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His lofty themes and stately eloquence made a profound impression.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He stood 6 ft 4 in (1.93 m) tall, with a massive frame.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His gestures were unconventional, but vigorous and impressive.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His literary style was florid, with much detail, allusion, and quotation, often from the Bible as well as the Greeks and Romans.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Following the annexation of Texas as a slave state in December, Sumner took an active role in the anti-slavery movement.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1847, he denounced the declaration of war against Mexico with such vigor that he was recognized as a leader of the "Conscience" faction of the Massachusetts Whig Party.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner also took an active role in other social causes.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He worked with Horace Mann to improve public education in Massachusetts, advocated for prison reform, and represented the plaintiffs in *Roberts v.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] City of Boston*, which challenged the legality of racial segregation in public schools.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner joined Black attorney Robert Morris in presenting that case, making it the first argued by an interracial legal team in American history.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Arguing before the Massachusetts Supreme Court, Sumner noted that schools for blacks were physically inferior and that segregation bred harmful psychological and sociological effects—arguments made in *Brown v.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Board of Education* over a century later.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner lost the case, but the Massachusetts General Court abolished school segregation in 1855.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1851, a coalition of Democratic and Free Soil legislators gained control of the Massachusetts General Court.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In exchange for Free Soil support for Democratic governor George Boutwell, the Free Soil Party named Sumner its choice for U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Despite the private agreement, conservative Democrats opposed his candidacy and called for a less radical candidate.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The impasse was broken after three months and Sumner was elected on a parliamentary technicality by a one-vote majority on April 24, 1851, in part thanks to the support of Senate President Henry Wilson.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His election marked a sharp break in Massachusetts politics, as his abolitionist politics contrasted sharply those of his best-known predecessor in the seat, Daniel Webster, one of the foremost supporters of the Compromise of 1850 and its Fugitive Slave Act.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] For the first few sessions, Sumner did not promote any of his controversial causes.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On August 26, 1852, he delivered his maiden speech, despite strenuous efforts to dissuade him.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] This oratorical effort was published as a pamphlet with the popular abolitionist motto, "Freedom National; Slavery Sectional," as its title.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In it, Sumner attacked the Fugitive Slave Act.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Though both major party platforms affirmed every provision of the Compromise of 1850 as final, including the Fugitive Slave Act, Sumner called for its repeal.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] For more than three hours, he denounced it as a violation of the Constitution, an affront to the public conscience, and an offence against divine law.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After his speech, a senator from Alabama urged that there be no reply: "The ravings of a maniac may sometimes be dangerous, but the barking of a puppy never did any harm." Sumner's outspoken opposition to slavery made him few friends in the Senate.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On May 19 and 20, 1856, during the civil unrest known as "Bleeding Kansas," Sumner denounced the Kansas–Nebraska Act in his "Crime against Kansas" speech.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The long speech argued for Kansas's immediate admission as a free state and denounced "Slave Power"—the political power of the slave owners.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner verbally attacked authors of the Act, Stephen A.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner's reference to slavery as Butler's "mistress" sought to highlight the sexual depravity of the institution—and possibly of Butler himself.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] An interview with a man who'd been enslaved by Butler, uncovered decades later by the historian Zaakir Tameez, suggests Butler fathered two children with a mistress he kept in his house, likely a slave.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Maintaining the analogy, Sumner presented himself as a modern Cicero, saving the American republic from anti-democratic conspirators.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On the afternoon of May 22, Representative Preston Brooks, Butler's first cousin once removed, confronted Sumner in the Senate chamber and beat him severely on the head, using a thick gutta-percha cane with a gold head.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner was knocked down and trapped under the heavy desk, which was bolted to the floor.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Blinded by his own blood, he staggered up the aisle and collapsed into unconsciousness.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Brooks continued to beat the motionless Sumner until his cane broke, at which point he continued to strike Sumner with the remaining piece.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Several other senators attempted to help Sumner, but were blocked by Laurence Keitt, who brandished a pistol and shouted, "Let them be!" The episode became a symbol of polarization in the antebellum period; Sumner became a martyr in the North and Brooks a hero in the South.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Thousands attended rallies in support of Sumner throughout the North.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Numerous African Americans wrote to Sumner after the caning, some of whom not only sympathized but also identified with him.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Brooks had described his attack on Sumner as a "flogging", as if to debase Sumner and imply he was no better than a slave.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] As a result, some Black Americans felt he too now bore the scars of slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] More than a million copies of Sumner's "Crime against Kansas" speech were distributed.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Ralph Waldo Emerson remarked, "I do not see how a barbarous community and a civilised community can constitute one state.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] I think we must get rid of slavery, or we must get rid of freedom." Conversely, Brooks was praised by Southern newspapers.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The *Richmond Enquirer* editorialized that Sumner should be caned "every morning" and Southerners sent Brooks hundreds of new canes in endorsement of his assault.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Southern lawmakers made rings out of the cane's remains, which they wore on neck chains to show solidarity with Brooks.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Historian William Gienapp has concluded that Brooks's "assault was of critical importance in transforming the struggling Republican party into a major political force." Theological and legal scholar William R.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In addition to head trauma, Sumner suffered "psychic wounds," now understood to be post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] When he spent months convalescing, his political enemies ridiculed him and accused him of cowardice for not resuming his duties.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The Massachusetts General Court reelected him in November 1856, believing that his vacant chair in the Senate chamber served as a powerful symbol of free speech and resistance to slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] When Sumner returned to the Senate in 1857, he was unable to last a day.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His doctors advised a sea voyage and "a complete separation from the cares and responsibilities that must beset him at home." He sailed for Europe and immediately found relief.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] During two months in Paris in the spring of 1857, he renewed friendships, especially with Thomas Gold Appleton, dined out frequently, and attended the opera.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His contacts there included Alexis de Tocqueville, poet Alphonse de Lamartine, former French Prime Minister François Guizot, Ivan Turgenev, and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner toured several countries, including Prussia and Scotland, before returning to Washington, where he spent only a few days in the Senate in December.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Both then and during several later attempts to return to work, he found himself exhausted just listening to Senate business.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He sailed once more for Europe on May 22, 1858, the second anniversary of Brooks's attack.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In Paris, prominent physician Charles-Édouard Brown-Séquard diagnosed Sumner's condition as spinal cord damage that he could treat by burning the skin along the spinal cord.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner chose to refuse anaesthesia, which was thought to reduce the effectiveness of the procedure.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Observers both at the time and since doubted Brown-Séquard's efforts were of value.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After spending weeks recovering from these treatments, Sumner resumed his touring, this time as far east as Dresden and Prague and south to Italy twice.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In France he visited Brittany and Normandy, as well as Montpellier.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1859, Sumner returned to the Senate permanently.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He attacked attempts to depict slavery as a benevolent institution, said it stifled economic development in the South, and that it left slaveholders reliant on "the bludgeon, the revolver, and the bowie-knife".
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He spent the summer rallying the anti-slavery forces for the election of 1860 and opposing talk of compromise.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After the Civil War began, Sumner was among the Radical Republicans who advocated immediate abolition of slavery and the destruction of the Southern planter class.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Although like-minded on slavery, the Radicals were loosely organized and disagreed on issues such as the tariff and currency.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Other Radicals in the Senate included Zachariah Chandler and Benjamin Wade.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After the fall of Fort Sumter in April 1861, Sumner, Chandler and Wade repeatedly visited President Abraham Lincoln at the White House to discuss slavery and the rebellion.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Throughout the war, Sumner had been the special champion of black Americans, being the most vigorous advocate of emancipation, of enlisting blacks in the Union Army, and of the establishment of the Freedmen's Bureau.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The Radicals desired the immediate emancipation of slaves and persistently lobbied for it as wartime policy, but Lincoln resisted, because it might prompt the border slave states to join the Confederacy.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Lincoln instead proposed a plan for gradual emancipation and compensation to slave owners, but consulted Sumner frequently.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Despite their disagreements, Lincoln called Sumner "my idea of a bishop" and an embodiment of the American people's conscience.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In May 1861, Sumner counseled Lincoln to make emancipation the war's primary objective.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He believed that military necessity would eventually force Lincoln's hand and that emancipation would give the Union higher moral standing, which would keep Britain from entering the Civil War on the Confederacy's side.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In October 1861, at the Massachusetts Republican Convention in Worcester, Sumner openly expressed his belief that slavery was the war's sole cause and that the Union government's primary objective was to end it.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner argued that Lincoln could command the Union Army to emancipate slaves under color of martial law.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In the conservative press, Sumner's speech was denounced as incendiary.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Conservative Massachusetts newspapers editorialized that he was mentally ill and a "candidate for the insane asylum," but the Radicals fully endorsed Sumner's speech, and he continued to advance his argument publicly.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] As an intermediate measure, the Radicals passed Confiscation Acts in 1861 and 1862 that allowed the military to emancipate slaves whom the Confederate military had impressed into service.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On January 1, 1863, Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, abolishing slavery in all Confederate territory.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The Thirteenth Amendment subsequently abolished chattel slavery.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After the withdrawal of Southern senators, Sumner became chair of the Committee on Foreign Relations in March 1861.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] As chair, he renewed his efforts for diplomatic recognition of Haiti.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Haiti had sought recognition since winning independence in 1804 but faced opposition from Southern senators.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In their absence, the United States recognized Haiti in 1862.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On November 8, 1861, the Union Navy warship USS *San Jacinto* intercepted the British steamer RMS *Trent*.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Two Confederate diplomats aboard were placed into port custody.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In response to the capture, the British government dispatched 8,000 troops to the Canada–United States border and sought to strengthen the Royal Navy.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Secretary of State William Seward believed the diplomats were contraband of war, but Sumner argued the men did not qualify as such because they were unarmed.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He favored their release along with an apology from the U.S. government towards Britain.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In the Senate, Sumner suppressed open debate in order to save the Lincoln administration from embarrassment.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On December 25, 1861, at Lincoln's invitation, Sumner addressed the cabinet.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He read letters from prominent British political figures, including Richard Cobden, John Bright, William Ewart Gladstone, and the Duke of Argyll as evidence that political sentiment in Britain supported the envoys' return to the British.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Lincoln quietly but reluctantly ordered the captives' release to British custody and apologized.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After the *Trent* affair, Sumner's reputation improved among conservative Northerners.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] As one of the Radical Republican leaders in the post-war Senate, Sumner fought to provide equal civil and voting rights for freedmen on the grounds that "consent of the governed" was a basic principle of American republicanism.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner's radical legal theory of Reconstruction proposed that nothing beyond the confines of the Constitution, read in light of the Declaration of Independence, restricted Congress's treatment of the rebelling states.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner emerged as an idealist and a champion for civil rights through this turbulent and controversial period.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He joined fellow Republicans in overriding President Andrew Johnson's vetoes, though his most radical ideas were not implemented.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner favored partial male suffrage with a literacy requirement for all Southerners in order to vote.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Instead, Congress imposed a loyalty requirement the following year; Sumner was strongly supportive.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner was a friend of Samuel Gridley Howe and a guiding force for the American Freedmen's Inquiry Commission, started in 1863.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He was one of the most prominent advocates for suffrage for blacks, along with free homesteads and free public schools.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His uncompromising attitude did not endear him to moderates, and his arrogance and inflexibility often inhibited his effectiveness as a legislator.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He was largely excluded from work on the Thirteenth Amendment, in part because he did not get along with Illinois Senator Lyman Trumbull, who chaired the Senate Judiciary Committee and did much of the work on it.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner introduced an alternative amendment that combined the Thirteenth Amendment with elements of the Fourteenth Amendment.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] It would have abolished slavery and declared that "all people are equal before the law." During Reconstruction, he often attacked civil rights legislation as inadequate and fought for legislation to give land to freed slaves and to mandate education for all, regardless of race, in the South.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He viewed segregation and slavery as two sides of the same coin.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He introduced a civil rights bill in 1872 to mandate equal accommodation in all public places and required suits brought under the bill to be argued in the federal courts.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The bill failed, but Sumner revived it in the next Congress, and on his deathbed begged visitors to see that it did not fail.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner repeatedly tried to remove the word "white" from naturalization laws.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He introduced bills to that effect in 1868 and 1869, but neither came to a vote.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On July 2, 1870, Sumner moved to amend a pending bill in a way that would strike the word "white" wherever in all Congressional acts pertaining to naturalization of immigrants.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner remained a champion of civil rights for blacks.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He co-authored the Civil Rights Act of 1875 with John Mercer Langston and introduced the bill in the Senate on May 13, 1870.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The bill passed a year after his death, in February 1875, and President Grant signed it into law on March 1.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] It was the last civil rights legislation for 82 years until the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1957.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The Supreme Court ruled it unconstitutional in 1883 when it decided a group of cases known as the Civil Rights Cases.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] When Johnson was impeached, Sumner voted for conviction at his trial.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Throughout March 1867, Secretary William H.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Seward and Russian representative Edouard de Stoeckl met in Washington, D.C., and negotiated a treaty for the annexation and sale of the Russian American territory of Alaska to the United States for $7,200,000.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] President Johnson submitted the treaty to Congress for ratification with Sumner's approval, and on April 9, his foreign relations committee approved and sent the treaty to the Senate.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In a three-hour speech, Sumner spoke in favor of the treaty on the Senate floor, describing Alaska's imperial history, natural resources, population, and climate.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner wanted to block British expansion from Canada, arguing that Alaska was geographically and financially strategic, especially for the Pacific Coast States.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He said Alaska would increase America's borders, spread republican institutions, and represent an act of friendship with Russia.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The treaty won its needed two-thirds majority by one vote.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The 1867 treaty neither formally recognized, categorised, nor compensated any native Alaskan Eskimos or Indians, referring to them only as "uncivilized tribes" under the control of Congress.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] By federal law, Native Alaskan tribes, including the Inuit, the Aleut, and the Athabascan, were entitled only to land that they inhabited.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] According to treaty, native Alaskan tribes were excluded from U.S. citizenship, but citizenship was available to Russian residents.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Creoles, persons of Russian and Indian descent, were considered Russian.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner said the new territory should be called by its Aleutian name, *Alaska*, meaning "great land." He advocated for free public education and equal protection laws for U.S. citizens in Alaska.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Personal achievements in 1867 included his election as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner was well regarded in the United Kingdom, but after the war he sacrificed his reputation in the U.K. with his stand on U.S. claims for British breaches of neutrality.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The U.S. had claims against Britain for the damage inflicted by Confederate raiding ships fitted out in British ports.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner held that since Britain had accorded the rights of belligerents to the Confederacy, it was responsible for extending the duration of the war and consequent losses.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He demanded $2,000,000,000 for these "national claims" in addition to $125,000,000 for damages from the raiders.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner did not expect that Britain ever would or could pay this sum, but he suggested that Britain turn over Canada as payment.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] This proposition offended many Britons, but was taken seriously by many Americans, including the Secretary of State, whose support for it nearly derailed the settlement with Great Britain in the months before the arbitration conference met at Geneva.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Lothrop Motley, the U.S. ambassador to Britain, causing him to disregard the instructions of Secretary of State Hamilton Fish on the matter.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] This offended President Grant, but while it would be given as the official reason for Motley's removal, was not really so pressing: the dismissal took place a year after Motley's alleged misbehavior, and the real reason was an act of spite by Grant against Sumner.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1869, President Grant, in an expansionist plan, looked into the annexation of a Caribbean island country, the Dominican Republic, then known as Santo Domingo.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Grant believed that the island's mineral resources would be valuable to the United States, and that African Americans repressed in the South would have a safe haven to which to migrate.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] A labor shortage in the South would force Southerners to be tolerant toward African Americans.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In July and November 1869, under Grant's authority and with the State Department's permission on the second trip, Orville Babcock, Grant's private secretary, secretly negotiated a treaty with President Buenaventura Báez of the Dominican Republic.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The initial treaty had not been authorized by the State Department, but the island nation was on the verge of a civil war between Báez and ex-President Marcos A.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Navy to keep the Dominican Republic free from invasion and civil war while the treaty negotiations took place.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] This military action was controversial since the naval protection was unauthorized by Congress.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The official treaty, drafted by Secretary of State Hamilton Fish in October 1869, annexed the Dominican Republic to the United States, gave eventual statehood, the lease of Samaná Bay for $150,000 yearly, and a $1,500,000 payment of the Dominican national debt.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In January 1870, in order to gain support for the treaty, Grant visited Sumner's Washington home and mistakenly believed that Sumner had consented to the treaty.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner said that he had only promised to give the treaty friendly consideration.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] This meeting led to bitter contention between Sumner and Grant.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The treaty was formally submitted to the United States Senate on January 10, 1870.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner, opposed to American imperialism in the Caribbean and fearful that annexation would lead to the conquest of the neighboring black republic of Haiti, became convinced that corruption lay behind the treaty, and that men close to Grant shared in the corruption.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] As chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, he initially withheld his opinion on the treaty on January 18, 1870.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner had been leaked information from Assistant Secretary of State Bancroft Davis that U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Naval ships were being used to protect Báez.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner's committee voted against annexation and, at Sumner's suggestion and possibly to save the party from an ugly fight or Grant from embarrassment, the Senate debated the treaty behind closed doors in executive session.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Grant persisted and sent messages to Congress in favor of annexation on March 14 and May 31, 1870.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In closed session, Sumner spoke out against the treaty, warning that there would be difficulty with the foreign nationals, noting the chronic rebellion on the island and the risk that the independence of Haiti, recognized by the U.S. in 1862, would be lost.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Navy as a protectorate was a violation of international law and unconstitutional.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Finally, on June 30, 1870, the treaty was voted on by the Senate and failed to gain the 2/3 majority required for passage.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The next day, Grant, feeling betrayed by Sumner, retaliated by ordering the dismissal of Sumner's close friend John Lothrop Motley, Ambassador to Britain.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] By autumn, Sumner's personal hostility to Grant was public knowledge, and he blamed the Secretary of State for failing to resign rather than let Grant have his way.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The two men, friends until then, became bitter enemies.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In December 1870, still fearful that Grant meant to acquire Santo Domingo somehow, Sumner gave a fiercely critical speech accusing him of usurpation and Babcock of unethical conduct.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Already Grant, supported by Fish, had initiated a campaign to depose Sumner from the chairmanship of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Grant also resented Sumner's superior manner.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Told that Sumner did not believe in the Bible, Grant supposedly said he was not surprised: "He didn't write it." As the rift between Grant and Sumner increased, Sumner's health began to decline.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Congress convened on March 4, 1871, senators affiliated with Grant, known as "New Radicals" voted to oust Sumner from the Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairmanship.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Like many other reformers, he decried the corruption in Grant's administration.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner believed that the civil rights program he championed could not be carried through by a corrupt government.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In 1872, he joined the Liberal Republican Party, which had been started by reformist Republicans such as Horace Greeley.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] For Sumner's civil rights bill they gave no support at all, but Sumner joined them because he had become convinced that the time had come for reconciliation, and that Democrats were sincere in declaring that they would abide by the Reconstruction settlement.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner never saw his support for civil rights as hostile to the South.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On the contrary, he had always contended that a guarantee of equality was the one condition essential for true reconciliation.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Unlike some other Radical Republicans, he had strongly opposed any hanging or imprisonment of Confederate leaders.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In December 1872, he introduced a Senate resolution providing that Civil War battle names should not appear as "battle honors" on the regimental flags of the U.S.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The proposal was not new: Sumner had offered a similar resolution on May 8, 1862, and in 1865 he had proposed that no painting hanging in the Capitol portray scenes from the Civil War, because, as he saw it, keeping alive the memories of a war between a people was barbarous.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His proposal did not affect the vast majority of battle-flags, as nearly all the regiments that fought had been state regiments, and these were not covered.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] But Sumner's idea was that any U.S. regiment that would in the future enlist Southerners as well as Northerners should not carry on its ensigns any insult to those who joined it.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] His resolution had no chance of passing, but its presentation offended Union army veterans.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] The Massachusetts legislature censured Sumner for giving "an insult to the loyal soldiery of the nation" and as "meeting the unqualified condemnation of the people of the Commonwealth." Poet John Greenleaf Whittier led an effort to rescind that censure the following year.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He succeeded early in 1874 with the help of abolitionist Joshua Bowen Smith, who was serving in the legislature that year.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner was able to hear the rescinding resolution presented to the Senate on the last day he was there.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On October 30, 1873, the *Virginius*, a munitions and troop transportation ship supporting the Cuban Rebellion and flying the U.S. flag, was captured by Spanish authorities.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] After a hasty trial in Santiago, Cuba, Spain executed 53 crew members, including American and British citizens.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner sympathized with the Cuban rebels and those executed by Spain, but refused to support U.S. military intervention or the annexation of Cuba.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On November 17, 1873, Sumner stated his views in an interview on the *Virginius* Affair at a local library in Boston.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He believed that although the ship was flying a U.S. flag, its mission was illegal.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Sumner, who opposed the Cuban insurgent neutrality of the Grant Administration, believed that the United States needed to support the First Spanish Republic.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] On November 28, 1873, Secretary of State Hamilton Fish, who coolly handled the incident amid national outcries for war, negotiated a peaceful settlement with Spanish President Emilio Castelar, and prevented war with Spain.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] Long ailing, Charles Sumner died of a heart attack at his home in Washington, D.C., on March 11, 1874, aged 63.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] He lay in state at the United States Capitol rotunda, the second senator (Henry Clay being the first, in 1852) and fourth person so honored.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] At his March 16 burial in Mount Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge, Massachusetts, the pallbearers included Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, Oliver Wendell Holmes, Ralph Waldo Emerson, and John Greenleaf Whittier.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p01] In the aftermath, Mississippi Senator Lucius Lamar's eulogy for Sumner was controversial enough considering his Southern heritage that the incident resulted in Lamar's inclusion in John F.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Contemporaries and historians have explored Sumner's personality and public career at length.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] But as perceptions of Reconstruction changed in recent years, so too have perceptions of Sumner.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Sumner's personality has also divided contemporaries and historians.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Just before he died, Sumner turned to his friend Ebenezer Rockwood Hoar.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Donald concludes that Sumner was a coward who avoided confrontations with his many enemies, whom he routinely insulted in prepared speeches.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] But in Donald's second volume, *Charles Sumner and the Rights of Man* (1970), he was more favorable to Sumner, and though critical, recognized his contributions to the accomplishments of Reconstruction.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Other contemporary civil rights figures and prominent historians similarly praised Sumner, including Frederick Douglass, Ralph Waldo Emerson and W.E.B.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] In the controversial 1915 film The Birth of a Nation Sumner was played by Sam De Grasse, though the role was minor and uncredited.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] In the 2012 film *Lincoln*, he was portrayed by actor John Hutton.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] He was played by Creed Bratton in the 2013 film *Saving Lincoln*.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Sumner was elected a member of the American Antiquarian Society in 1843.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] He served on the society's board of councilors from 1852 to 1853, and later in life served as the society's secretary of foreign correspondence from 1867 to 1874.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Sumner was a bachelor for most of his life and might have been gay.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] For years, he enjoyed a romantic friendship with physician and fellow abolitionist Samuel Gridley Howe, spending extensive time with Howe as a young man and maintaining a correspondence with him throughout their lives.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] "There is something at the bottom of my heart & on my lips always for you," Sumner once told Howe.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Later, when Sumner was elected to the Senate, Howe burned many letters from his friend, lest they be seen "by unfriendly eyes." Throughout his life, Howe regularly burned or shredded correspondence with Sumner, and Julia discarded even more letters between the two after Howe's death.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] In the years leading up to the Civil War, political opponents such as Sen.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Andrew Butler of South Carolina mocked Sumner's status as a bachelor, implying he fantasized about Black women.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] After years of bachelorhood, Sumner began courting Alice Mason Hooper, the widowed daughter-in-law of Massachusetts Representative Samuel Hooper in 1866, and they married that October.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Sumner could not respond to his wife's humor, and Alice had a ferocious temper.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] That winter, Alice began going out to public events with Prussian diplomat Friedrich von Holstein.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] This caused gossip in Washington, but Alice refused to stop seeing Holstein.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] When Holstein was recalled to Prussia in the spring of 1867, Alice accused Sumner of engineering the action, which Sumner denied.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] Sumner's enemies used the affair to attack Sumner's manhood, calling him "The Great Impotency." The situation depressed and embarrassed Sumner.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] He obtained an uncontested divorce on the grounds of desertion on May 10, 1873.
[src:charles-sumner/charles-sumner-p02] There is a statue of Sumner in Cambridge, Massachusetts by sculptor Anne Whitney and another statue of Sumner in Boston, Massachusetts by sculptor Thomas Ball.
